/    \\<br> //// sorr\\ can/t po/t //o/ut supernova<br>//// thro\\\\ a// th/s Starlink garb\\ge/<br>///    //////\\\\ //  / // // sor/////\\\\\\\\\\\\","favorite_count":"25","retweet_count":"9"},{"created_at":"Mon Apr 25 08:40:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1518510130022830081","full_text":"McNaught measures a magnitude of M 3.1 from Siding Spring","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Apr 24 22:00:29 +0000 2022","id_str":"1518349183400529920","full_text":"B magnitude measured in South Africa to be 4.7","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Apr 24 10:05:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1518169131064991745","full_text":"Garradd measures magnitude from Tamsworth, N.S.W.: M 3.0","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Apr 23 09:40:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1517800454356357120","full_text":"McNaught measures magnitude from Siding Spring to be M 3.1","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Apr 21 10:20:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1517085743159681024","full_text":"McNaught takes a measurement of M 3.1 from Siding Spring","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 22 18:10:36 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506332533180489737","full_text":"OK, so, why is neutrino transport different from other radiation transport?  Because photons only go short distances.  If your simulation-code predicts a jump in temperature at radius r, it basically has to calculate how that affects r-dr and r+dr in the next timestep.<br>1/13","favorite_count":"14","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 22 17:00:37 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506314918152179712","full_text":"a) I do not think I have ever used the diskette.  It purports to contains codes call \"ZAMS\" (for ZAMS) and \"PULS\" (for asteroseismology)<br>b) The musical score on the cover is a nice Easter egg","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 22 16:22:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506305210716667910","full_text":"It turns out, neutrinos throw a HUGE wrench into your differential equation solving. Interestingly, though, it's a wrench we've seen somewhere before ... but that'll be the next thread.<br>9/9","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 22 16:21:57 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506305189229252609","full_text":"In the 1980s, we became LESS OPTIMISTIC about 1D neutrino-transport simulations because the models STILL DON'T EXPLODE. But we're still refining them. (2D simulations are still years away.) Maybe it's just a small tweak somewhere. <br>8/9","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 22 16:21:52 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506305167611904009","full_text":"But the other fun ingredient is OUR FRIEND THE NEUTRINO. Neutrinos generated in one place can deposit their energy FAR AWAY (pointed out by Colgate and White 1966).   In the 1970s, we were optimistic that adding neutrinos to 1D simulations will explain supernovae.<br>7/9","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 22 16:21:47 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506305145734410241","full_text":"The thing is, we're stuck computing everything in one dimension.  You can divide your star into spherical shells, and compute ONLY the inward/outward components of forces.  We'll pretend motion in latitude or longitude is forbidden by spherical symmetry.<br>6/9","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 22 16:21:41 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506305123399737350","full_text":"One thing that COULD screw this up are magnetic fields---they're long range, not short range.  Unfortunately they're also very 3D; in 1985 people worry about them (Mueller and Hillebrandt 1979) but do not, I think, have a real modeling strategy.<br>5/9","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 22 16:21:36 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506305101908041734","full_text":"If you know the current state (P/V/T/composition) of the gas at position r, you can find the rate-of-change of the gas at r and at r +/- dr. If supernovae exploded \"acoustic mechanism\" we'd have seen it in the 60s by refining the details of this hydro model.  But no.<br>4/9","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 22 16:21:31 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506305080286453765","full_text":"A density/temperature/pressure relation was hammered out in the 30s (Eddington/Chandrasekhar/Jeans/Saha/Milne) and the energy source in the 40s (Fowler/Hoyle/Burbidge/Burbidge/Bethe).  Those are the ingredients of ordinary hydrodynamic differential equations!  Easy!<br>3/9","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 22 16:21:26 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506305058631294981","full_text":"So, what are the ingredients of a supernova model?  At any given place in the star, you have a fluid; if you know its temperature and density you know its pressure. If there's a pressure gradient, it'll exert a force and the fluid will accelerate. That's 19th century (Lane).<br>2/9","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 22 16:21:21 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506305036904714253","full_text":"Let's talk about SUPERNOVA EXPLOSION THEORY in 1987, a topic covered by hundreds of articles going back 20 years; by dozens of review articles; by at least a few meta-review articles complaining that the preexisting reviews are too complex; and by A FEW 280-CHAR TWEETS UGH<br>1/9","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 22 14:45:03 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506280803625492487","full_text":"Before we study exploding stars, we have to study non-exploding stars. The science of stellar interiors *in hydrostatic equilibrium* is very very old.  IIRC my very first numerical-astro homework was to solve (in Fortran) the Lane-Emden equation---which dates to 1870! <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1506280803625492487-FOdiZ9cWYAwZCWp.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1506280803625492487-FOdiZ9cWYAwZCWp.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1506280803625492487-FOdiZ_GWYBAnmLi.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1506280803625492487-FOdiZ_GWYBAnmLi.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"45","retweet_count":"6"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 22 14:25:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506275765628903425","full_text":"Visual magnitude estimate from R.H. McNaught at Coonabarabran, N.S.W.: M 4.1","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 21 22:00:42 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506028050437312514","full_text":"B magnitude measured in South Africa at magnitude 5.6","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 21 20:16:03 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506001713743945732","full_text":"And that's maybe half of the early-1987 literature JUST on this new neutrino mass constraint.   There's a ton of other neutrino physics, but that's another thread.<br>13/13","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 21 20:15:58 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506001691887509505","full_text":"Arafane and Fukugita submitted maybe the first PhysRevLetters on 1987A theory (received 23 March)  <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1103/PhysRevLett.59.367\">https://doi.org/10.1103/PhysRevLett.59.367</a>, giving m &lt; 15 eV conservatively and m &lt; 5 eV with some assumptions.  To illustrate the level of hyperdetail: <br>12/13 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1506001691887509505-FOZkju_XMAckGBC.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1506001691887509505-FOZkju_XMAckGBC.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 21 20:15:52 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506001668688822273","full_text":"The outlier here (in time and in, uh, outcome) is Hillebrandt et. al.; their very early March 4 letter to A&amp;A 1987A%26A...177L..41H claims to have measured 15 eV (+8/-4) from an energy-ordering among the Mont Blanc neutrinos (!!). <br>11/13","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 21 20:15:47 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506001647188824065","full_text":"Burrows and Lattimer submit their m &lt; 6.5 eV calculation to ApJ on April 6.<br>10/13","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 21 20:15:42 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506001625785241610","full_text":"Arnett and Rosner will submit theirs to PRL on April 8, explicitly saying they think Mont Blanc is noise.<br>9/13","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 21 20:15:37 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506001603572162560","full_text":"Matts Roos's version, presented at Moriond (and with an author sketch (!?) in the proceedings?) suggests m &lt; 5 eV <br>8/13 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1506001603572162560-FOZkekhXoAs9kFG.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1506001603572162560-FOZkekhXoAs9kFG.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 21 20:15:31 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506001579878588421","full_text":"Go ahead, calculate the limits yourself, everyone is doing it!  You have to make some assumptions about the burst?  Sure, make some!  See what happens!<br>7/13","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 21 20:15:25 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506001556533096449","full_text":"(Note: previously-published lab experiments have used precision tritium beta decay spectroscopy to tell us the electron neutrino mass is m &lt; 18 eV.  In 2022, tritium endpoint spectroscopy will be your humble Twitter host's pet project.) <br>6/13","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 21 20:15:20 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506001534794051590","full_text":"In relativity, \"everything travels at exactly the speed limit\" is characteristic of massless particles, like photons.  \"everything travels at VERY NEARLY the speed limit\" is characteristic of very LOW MASS particles.  So SN1987A tells us neutrinos are low mass.  How low?<br>5/13","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 21 20:15:15 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506001513348481026","full_text":"If neutrinos weighed as much as electrons, the high-energy events would have arrived YEARS after the photons; the low energy events would have been delayed by CENTURIES.  It wouldn't have looked like a burst at all.<br>4/13","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 21 20:15:10 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506001491856924675","full_text":"The neutrino's all-at-the-same-time arrival means they traveled at VERY NEARLY EXACTLY the same speed, despite their huge range of energies. (Caveat: that's IF they were emitted all at once, an issue that is being gamed out on every theory-department blackboard on Earth.)<br>3/13","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 21 20:15:05 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506001470285561864","full_text":"After 158,000 years of travel, even a tiny SPEED difference means a huge ARRIVAL TIME difference.  This is the opposite of Driver's Ed where they tell you that running red lights doesn't get you there appreciably earlier. <br>2/13","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 21 20:15:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506001448626274314","full_text":"One thing was obvious to everyone: the neutrinos arrived in a burst.  High energy (50 MeV) or low energy (10 MeV), they all arrived within 10--12 seconds.  See why that's weird?  A NEUTRINO MASS THREAD: <br>1/13","favorite_count":"13","retweet_count":"5"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 21 17:00:23 +0000 2022","id_str":"1505952473005002754","full_text":"People are still arguing about (a) whether Mont Blanc's neutrinos are a real signal or not, and (b) whether Kamiokande saw one long burst, two short bursts, or one short burst followed by some noise.","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 21 16:49:59 +0000 2022","id_str":"1505949857210507265","full_text":"For scale: <br>500th most populous US city: Mount Vernon, NY<br>500th highest US box office gross: Borat<br>500th place on career MLB hits: Blue Jays stalwart Shannon Stewart <br>500th most-cited paper on INSPIRE: Astrophys.J.Lett. 545 (2000), Hanany et al on the MAXIMA-1 CMB map","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 21 16:00:19 +0000 2022","id_str":"1505937356347645956","full_text":"People are still arguing about WHICH STAR exploded, especially driven by Sonneborn and Kirschner's report (IAUC 4333) that they think the OG Sanduleak -69 202 is STILL THERE, visible in the UV. (David Arnett sounds a bit salty about this.) <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1505937356347645956-FOYqC45WUAgqeP4.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1505937356347645956-FOYqC45WUAgqeP4.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 21 15:00:18 +0000 2022","id_str":"1505922253447438340","full_text":"At Day 26, 1987A is maybe the 500th brightest object in the sky.  Its photosphere is 100 AU in diameter---the size of the whole solar system (including Pluto because it's 1987).   (Clarification: this is big.) The progenitor's diameter was 0.4 AU. (Also big.)","favorite_count":"10","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 21 14:30:03 +0000 2022","id_str":"1505914641964318726","full_text":"For the past three weeks we've been tweeting about observations.  Of course the astro and particle theory communities have been busy trying to learn something from them!  This week, we'll focus on the earliest theory/analysis/interpretation.","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 21 14:01:36 +0000 2022","id_str":"1505907482685853698","full_text":"March 21, 1987.  The Vernal Equinox edition of the Canadian Astronomical Society newsletter CASCA highlights the liminal nature of 1987 computing:  you're on BITNET ... but you need to send paper mail to tell people that. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1505907482685853698-FOYO4BzX0AQmnRN.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1505907482685853698-FOYO4BzX0AQmnRN.png\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1505907482685853698-FOYO4BmXMAMFMjF.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1505907482685853698-FOYO4BmXMAMFMjF.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 21 02:51:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1505738717385961474","full_text":"Happy equinox! @RealTime1987Equinox","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Mar 20 11:35:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1505508206289764357","full_text":"Beresford takes magnitude measurement: M 3.9","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Sun Mar 20 10:50:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1505496882860249091","full_text":"McNaught takes magnitude measurement: M 4.0","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Mar 19 12:30:07 +0000 2022","id_str":"1505159684466040837","full_text":"Beresford takes magnitude measurement: M 4.0","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Mar 19 09:25:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1505113101934514179","full_text":"McNaught takes magnitude measurement: M 4.1","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Mar 19 01:04:23 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504987113468608520","full_text":"@DMOPalmer But wait, maybe you're right.  I thought I'd seen a source specifying a particular SEC tube as the FES readout but I may have gotten it mixed up with the spectrometer cameras.","favorite_count":"0","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 18 22:00:35 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504940855328653323","full_text":"B magnitude measured in South Africa: M 5.7","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 18 20:00:38 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504910669698813959","full_text":"(Your ground-based telescope's guide camera, in 1987, may well still be a vidicon, but if it does any autoguiding it's probably reading and processing raster image data. Hubble (3y to launch!) will have analog-output fine guidance---no CCDs, just PMTs and optomechanics!)<br>6/6 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1504910669698813959-FOKER5IWUAILh0N.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1504910669698813959-FOKER5IWUAILh0N.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 18 20:00:32 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504910646500016138","full_text":"(The IUE vidicon can do conventional raster imaging of a 16-arcmin field with 8 arcsec resolution; or it can do this target-lock (\"prime\") mode; or (if you expect a M&lt;5 star in the field) you can tell the vidicon to raster until it finds it, then switch to prime mode.) <br>5/6 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul></ul></div>","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 18 20:00:17 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504910584130809859","full_text":"... if, for example, your vidicon image has one bright star in it you want to use for guiding.  You can scan your readout beam over this star's charge-image over and over (in a + shape) and with very little computation power you can tell if the star's position has changed.  <br>4/6","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 18 20:00:12 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504910562307850250","full_text":"then you can steer an electron beam onto any point on that surface and read it out its charge.  If you just raster-scan that electron beam, it's a normal analog video camera.  BUT you can also custom-steer the readout beam ... <br>3/6","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 18 20:00:06 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504910538203176971","full_text":"The IUE observing guide calls it an \"image dissector\" but I think it's actually a Secondary Electron Conduction (SEC) vidicon. You image starlight onto the photocathode, out pop photoelectrons. Those bombard the SEC surface and make an electric-charge image.<br>2/6 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1504910538203176971-FOKEKPNXsAk-nr1.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1504910538203176971-FOKEKPNXsAk-nr1.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 18 20:00:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504910513779654657","full_text":"The International Ultraviolet Explorer gets visual magnitudes from its \"fine error sensor\".  Launched in the pre-CCD era, what even is that?  Like all pre-CCD video cameras (including science cameras) it's some sort of vidicon tube!  <br>1/6 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1504910513779654657-FOKEIuCWQA0HfHQ.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1504910513779654657-FOKEIuCWQA0HfHQ.png\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1504910513779654657-FOKEIukX0AgVxkz.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1504910513779654657-FOKEIukX0AgVxkz.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1504910513779654657-FOKEIv4XMAQf1nl.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1504910513779654657-FOKEIv4XMAQf1nl.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 18 17:40:03 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504875291331776519","full_text":"Here's the rest of La Silla's Feb/Mar schedule: the GPO astrograph, the 1.4 m Danish, and the 90 cm Dutch telescopes. (Nobody is scheduled for the 50-cm Danish or 61-cm Bochum.) <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1504875291331776519-FOJkGiUWQAcuWCg.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1504875291331776519-FOJkGiUWQAcuWCg.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 18 17:20:03 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504870256837373952","full_text":"Here are visitors scheduled at the 1.4m Coud√© Auxiliary Telescope (a weird alt-alt mounted gizmo whose sort-of-Naysmith-like focus feeds the spectrometer in the 3.6m Coud√© room), the 1-m Photometric Telescope, and the 50 cm ESO photometric telescope. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1504870256837373952-FOJfhhHWUAcWwf3.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1504870256837373952-FOJfhhHWUAcWwf3.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1504870256837373952-FOJfhhSXEAkIbtl.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1504870256837373952-FOJfhhSXEAkIbtl.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1504870256837373952-FOJfhfSXEA0DPtT.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1504870256837373952-FOJfhfSXEA0DPtT.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 18 17:01:03 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504865475360141318","full_text":"The September 1986 issue of the @ESO Messenger lists all the expected visiting observers at La Silla through this April.  Who's at the ESO 3.6, 2.2, and 1.5-m?  Tag yourself!  Tag your friends! <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1504865475360141318-FOJbLK1WUAEI8ci.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1504865475360141318-FOJbLK1WUAEI8ci.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1504865475360141318-FOJbLJoXIAI8lNg.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1504865475360141318-FOJbLJoXIAI8lNg.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1504865475360141318-FOJbLLbX0AI5Szz.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1504865475360141318-FOJbLLbX0AI5Szz.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 18 13:01:04 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504805085502709782","full_text":"It's March 18, 1987. You spent the past week carefully positioning your spectrometer to avoid 1987A's bluer companion? Alex Filippenko pops up in IAUC 4347 to say: that's just blue from 1987A's chromatic atmospheric refraction, citing his grad-school paper 1982PASP...94..715F ü§¶‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1504805085502709782-FOIkQElWQAInI9B.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1504805085502709782-FOIkQElWQAInI9B.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"12","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 18 02:25:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504645019612987393","full_text":"According to IUE data, 1987A is no longer detectable in 120-200nm range but is brighter than ever in visible range.","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 17 22:00:36 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504578474006261767","full_text":"B magnitude was measured in South Africa to be 5.7","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 17 17:42:32 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504513528664772622","full_text":"Part of it is not \"nationalism\" but \"telescope and cameras last for decades\".  The \"Dutch Telescope\" is literally the same one Theodore Walraven (1916--2008) invented these passbands on in South Africa in 1958.","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 17 15:01:05 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504472900367134724","full_text":"I don't have a photo or diagram of the previous tweet's cameras, but here's the fast Multi-Channel Multi-Color Photometer (MCCP) currently on the ESO 1-m. (It took UVBRI data on 1987A on 2/28 only; then small telescopes took over. The R and I bands seem to have this week off.) <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1504472900367134724-FOD2HuHVEAEXeoC.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1504472900367134724-FOD2HuHVEAEXeoC.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1504472900367134724-FOD2IMEVUAYzwJh.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1504472900367134724-FOD2IMEVUAYzwJh.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 17 14:00:36 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504457679720390666","full_text":"It's March 16th. At La Silla, the all-singing, all-dancing, all-photometric systems show is still playing: Cousins (5  colors), Geneva (7), Stromgren (4+HŒ≤), Walraven (5).  Is photometry always this nationalistic?  Swiss/Danish/Dutch filter sets for Swiss/Danish/Dutch telescopes? <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1504457679720390666-FODoSXqWUAQwsBl.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1504457679720390666-FODoSXqWUAQwsBl.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 17 12:01:43 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504427758893641732","full_text":"In Adelaide, S. Australia Beresford takes a magnitude measurement: M 4.0","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 17 11:45:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504423561095782400","full_text":"Seargent makes visual magnitude measurement at The Entrance, N.S.W.: M 4.1","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 17 09:40:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504392102347739136","full_text":"G. Garradd makes magnitude measurement at Tamworth, N.S.W.: M 4.4","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 16 14:56:40 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504109400868458506","full_text":"To wrap up: IMB timestamped the SN1987A burst with modern methods.  Kamiokande agrees, within the range of a hilariously human error bar.  Baksan agrees, if we're not being pessimistic about the range of possible computer clock freakouts.  Mont Blanc?  STILL WEIRD.<br><br>20/20","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 16 14:56:35 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504109379288768513","full_text":"(But Baksan's five-neutrino event itself is not insane, it's not insane to say it's at the right time, and though it's on the high end of SN1987A flux estimation, it doesn't break anything (Loredo &amp; Lamb, PhysRevD 65 2002))<br>19/20","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 16 14:56:30 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504109357717467142","full_text":"(In fact you can dig deeper in the literature and find a HUGE number of weird time-correlation claims: between neutrino detectors, gravity-wave sensors, gravity-wave sensors with a long history of false alarms, you name it. I'm not going to livetweet all of it.) <br>18/20","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 16 14:56:25 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504109336221691909","full_text":"I will pay (and you) the courtesy of addressing it: (a) an INSANE suite of new physics is implied if this correlation were real (b) Extraordinary Claims Require Extraordinary Evidence (c) the JETP analysis is thin and smells of simple P-hacking.<br>17/20","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 16 14:56:20 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504109314600022017","full_text":"You'll see Baksan conference talks saying that this \"lucky effect\" has \"confirmed\" the Baksan clock shift.  WHAT.  The wider literature, while mostly accepting the Baksan five-event signal, has largely ignored THAT detail ... <br>16/20","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 16 14:56:15 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504109292919660548","full_text":"Baksan people will later start making strange claim (JETP Letters 49:9 (4820)) that radioactivity (??) and muons (?!) at Baksan and LSD are time-correlated for some hours on Feb 23, particularly with Baksan events somewhat-more-likely to occur 30s before LSD events (!!!!!!)<br>15/20","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 16 14:56:09 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504109271377760257","full_text":"In fact Baksan's five events are timestamped about 30 seconds after IMB's eight.  \"OK fine that's consistent\" you might say, and ... it is? But we're very far from the \"blind\" analysis conditions by which IMB and K-II (and Mont Blanc) found and timestamped their bursts.<br>14/20","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 16 14:56:04 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504109249223405569","full_text":"(In my mind, that's an awfully precise and specific range of possibilities to assign to a clock that might be more accurately described as \"sort of freaking out and unreliable\".)<br><br>13/20 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1504109249223405569-FN-rZE0XoBEl2lz.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1504109249223405569-FN-rZE0XoBEl2lz.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 16 14:55:59 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504109225995382792","full_text":"Their published interpretation is that an \"unexplained\" 54 second jump occurred, and the only uncertainty is whether it occurred before or after this clock timestamped the supernova events, or some jumping before and some after.  So they claim to know the time \"-54/+2 s\"<br>12/20 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1504109225995382792-FN-rXqYWYAsGl-Y.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1504109225995382792-FN-rXqYWYAsGl-Y.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"11","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 16 14:55:53 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504109201609707524","full_text":"Baksan's timing is weird.  Their computer clock was expected to be accurate to +/- 2s, they did occasionally sync it to an external signal.  One sync on Feb 17. Another on March 11---but it showed the computer clock had gained 54 seconds.  No idea when or how.<br>11/20","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 16 14:55:48 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504109180185161730","full_text":"So remember that the Baksan scintillator experiment?  With a five-neutrino signal at about the Kamiokande/IMB time?<br>10/20","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 16 14:55:43 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504109158496444419","full_text":"On later comparison, the Kamiokande and IMB data burst timestamps WERE within a few seconds, so the shifter HAD done his job quickly.  (But it's NOT correct to report that as K-II's global timing error, a subtlety that physics lab instructors should ALSO teach.) <br>9/20","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 16 14:55:37 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504109136912568332","full_text":"It would have been NICE if Kamiokande could have come back a few days later and repeated the sync process more carefully---the computer clock doesn't drift THAT fast---but alas a Feb 26 power outage reset the computer and lost the clock state.<br>8/20","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 16 14:55:32 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504109115408326673","full_text":"and THAT report is the beginning and the end of the \"+/- 1m\" Kamiokande quotes as their timing error.  (I would like to commend this anecdote in particular to every physics lab instructor who has to teach students How Do We Estimate Error Bars).<br>7/20","favorite_count":"11","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 16 14:55:27 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504109093719781378","full_text":"Weeks after the supernova, this shifter was asked to recall EXACTLY how the time-sync process had gone down that day.  Had he typed quickly or slowly?  Type *while* holding the phone or *after* hanging up?  \"Much less than a minute delay\" is the best he could recall ...<br>6/20","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 16 14:55:22 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504109071678554121","full_text":"At Kamiokande, it's funny.  The computer gets a once-per-day update, but it's done OVER THE PHONE, by a human.  Whoever is on shift, once a day, made a PHONE CALL to a TIME SERVICE, then typed the current time into the computer.  How accurate can that be? <br>5/20 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1504109071678554121-FN-rOtkXEAwtl-N.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1504109071678554121-FN-rOtkXEAwtl-N.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 16 14:55:16 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504109048173629442","full_text":"At IMB, their CAMAC crate has a 13 MHz input clock synced to WWVB (<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WWVB\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WWVB</a>), a NIST radio time service.  It's reliable to +/- 5ms. (I'm not sure how---phone lines to the surface?)<br>4/20","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 16 14:55:11 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504109026136801286","full_text":"In 2022, your computer is probably syncing its clock to a NIST-calibrated network time server and/or GPS chip occasionally.  In 1987, it's just counting the ticks on its internal quartz oscillator, like a wristwatch or a microwave or a VCR.  Whose clocks were set right? <br>3/20 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1504109026136801286-FN-rMEEX0AkjHjO.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1504109026136801286-FN-rMEEX0AkjHjO.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 16 14:55:05 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504109001667235842","full_text":"So, when exactly was the neutrino burst, and how do we know?  Every event written to tape, on every detector, got timestamped---usually the data acquisition computer consults its internal clock.  <br>2/20","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 16 14:55:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504108979986784262","full_text":"We're getting CLOSE to wrapping up the neutrino story.  To get back to Baksan, Russia, I want to talk about timing AGAIN.  Not the shape or duration of the burst, but the start time.  This is, as you may have guessed, a THREAD: <br>1/20","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 16 12:01:30 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504065318511071234","full_text":"Visual magnitude measurement from Beresford: M 4.0","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 16 10:05:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1504036008005935104","full_text":"Seargent makes another magnitude measurement: M 4.0","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 15 20:00:39 +0000 2022","id_str":"1503823509864300556","full_text":"In 1987 there's actually A FIFTH large supernova-ready neutrino detector.  Artemovsk Scintillator Detector (1977--2022?) a 100-t scintillator tank in a salt mine in modern-day üá∫üá¶ Bakhmut, Donetsk, Ukraine üá∫üá¶.  Unfortunately Feb 23 was during some maintenance downtime. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1503823509864300556-FN6ngrDXMAYXImb.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1503823509864300556-FN6ngrDXMAYXImb.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"13","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 15 17:01:31 +0000 2022","id_str":"1503778433154826246","full_text":"It's March 15th, 1987.  Jaymie Matthews says Las Campanas is swarming with reporters, including a NOVA documentary crew with so many xenon floodlights it's hard to do astronomy. <br> <a href=\"https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1447020/\">https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1447020/</a>","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 15 13:30:43 +0000 2022","id_str":"1503725380573843461","full_text":"@ghphotonics So the new hastily-configured system, which started operations March 7, has to read out one Pockels cell state and use a shutter to block the other.  A 20-second exposure gets 4 seconds of useful light and takes 80 seconds to read out but STILL BETTER THAN ICPS.<br>7/7 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1503725380573843461-FN5OQ6cWUAUDCfU.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1503725380573843461-FN5OQ6cWUAUDCfU.png\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1503725380573843461-FN5OQ8SXMAUmTuv.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1503725380573843461-FN5OQ8SXMAUmTuv.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 15 13:30:37 +0000 2022","id_str":"1503725356519497730","full_text":"@ghphotonics The Pockels cell is normally used to SWITCH polarizations once per second. CCDs read out sloooooowly. You don't want a CCD sitting there collecting both polarizations on top of each other, that's what we call \"spectro-not-actually-polarimetry\"<br>6/7","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 15 13:30:32 +0000 2022","id_str":"1503725334667145221","full_text":"@ghphotonics Problem is, it saturates horribly with stars brighter than M=14.  The AAT limped along with this---filtering SN1987A down to a few photons per second per pixel---until March 7 when (see (see 1988MNRAS.231..695C) AAT swapped the ICPS for a CCD (GEC, top right). Problem: <br>5/7 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1503725334667145221-FN5OOQ5XsAMmzIO.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1503725334667145221-FN5OOQ5XsAMmzIO.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 15 13:30:26 +0000 2022","id_str":"1503725310168248320","full_text":"@ghphotonics The 2nd neat thing is that the AAT has an Image Photon Counting Sensor, a Rube-Goldberg-sounding gizmo from the pre-CCD era; imagine pointing a TV camera into a pair of night-vision goggles.  You get single-photon sensitivity AND computer readout.<br>4/7 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1503725310168248320-FN5OMyvWUAUFZAx.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1503725310168248320-FN5OMyvWUAUFZAx.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 15 13:30:20 +0000 2022","id_str":"1503725285207851010","full_text":"@ghphotonics You put a high voltage across the crystal, it ROTATES the light polarization.  The spectrometer channel that used to get Q now gets U and vice-versa. (Look up \"Stokes parameters\" to learn what Q and U mean). <br>3/7","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 15 13:30:15 +0000 2022","id_str":"1503725263573729290","full_text":"The calcite in the beam here always splits light's two polarizations and sends them to two spectrometer channels. The magical new here is a crystal called KD*P (made by Cleveland Crystals, now @ghphotonics) which exhibits the electro-optic \"Pockels Effect\".  <br>2/7","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 15 13:30:08 +0000 2022","id_str":"1503725233097920517","full_text":"Need a break from neutrinos?  Let's check in with the astronomers.  Here's the instrument that the Anglo-Australian Telescope has been used for spectropolarimetry since 1984.  (from McLean, 1984MNRAS.209..655M) <br>1/7 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1503725233097920517-FN5OGv_XEAcxnU2.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1503725233097920517-FN5OGv_XEAcxnU2.png\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1503725233097920517-FN5OGxWWUAIi1z7.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1503725233097920517-FN5OGxWWUAIi1z7.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"15","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 15 11:05:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1503688715574693891","full_text":"Visual magnitude measurement from Garradd in Tamworth, N.S.W.: M 4.3","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 15 10:35:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1503681165647138817","full_text":"D. Seargent makes magnitude measurement at The Entrance, N.S.W.: M 4.0","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 14 22:00:35 +0000 2022","id_str":"1503491305783152651","full_text":"B magnitude was measured in South Africa: M 5.7","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 14 17:00:46 +0000 2022","id_str":"1503415853160833035","full_text":"(Although it occurs to me to wonder: could some obsessive analog magnetic-tape forensics tell whether a few inches of tape had undergone an extra write pass, as from a retry?  The tape, of course, still exists.)  <br>9/9 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1503415853160833035-FN00wH-XMAMg9CB.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1503415853160833035-FN00wH-XMAMg9CB.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"13","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 14 17:00:40 +0000 2022","id_str":"1503415829886607365","full_text":"As was the case with \"what did Mont Blanc see?\" and \"why was the Baksan time a bit off?\":  We may never know!  \"How much should you read into the 7-second gap?\", you ask?    <br>8/9 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1503415829886607365-FN00usKXsAccF7S.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1503415829886607365-FN00usKXsAccF7S.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 14 17:00:34 +0000 2022","id_str":"1503415805479903235","full_text":"The idea that this particular hardware blip HAPPENED to land in the MIDDLE of the supernova of the century? That's got its own improbability factor, unless data errors can be caused by a sudden increase in the event rate.  <br>7/9","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 14 17:00:29 +0000 2022","id_str":"1503415784013549571","full_text":"The seven-second gap was much discussed (both as a statistical artifact and as a supernova-physics-signal) 1987--2021, but AFAICT Oyama's 2021 (2021!) work is the first to point out this tiny hardware detail.   <br>6/9","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 14 17:00:24 +0000 2022","id_str":"1503415761422934020","full_text":"For example, the TAPE had a WRITE ERROR, which would prompt it to pause, rewind (6250 bytes per inch on 2400' reels), and retry.  Oyama recalls that 10-second retries happened \"about once an hour\"; less often if the write heads were kept extra clean.<br>5/9 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1503415761422934020-FN00quuWYAEjZWB.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1503415761422934020-FN00quuWYAEjZWB.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 14 17:00:18 +0000 2022","id_str":"1503415736655613957","full_text":"Kamiokande's data went to a PDP/11-60, then to magnetic tape, via a tiny I/O buffer.  Detector sends data to buffer memory, buffer memory goes to tape.  If new data comes in when the buffer was already full, it just ... vanishes.   The buffer might be full!  Why?  <br>4/9 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1503415736655613957-FN00pPZWQAsg3Rm.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1503415736655613957-FN00pPZWQAsg3Rm.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 14 17:00:12 +0000 2022","id_str":"1503415711582015489","full_text":"Note Kamiokande saw NOTHING in this window. No 1987A nus.  No muons (average 0.37 events per sec). No low-energy radioactivity (average 0.15/sec). It's all PLAUSIBLE as ordinary unlucky stats, but Oyama (right) suggests another explanation<br>in <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2108.01783\">https://arxiv.org/abs/2108.01783</a>, namely:<br>3/9 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1503415711582015489-FN00n0mXIAAuMWr.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1503415711582015489-FN00n0mXIAAuMWr.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 14 17:00:06 +0000 2022","id_str":"1503415687234134020","full_text":"That seven second gap is weird.  Did the SN1987A flux really turn sharply off, or down, after the first two seconds?  If it's not \"off\" but \"down\", even to a one-per-second-ish mean, then it required some bad luck not to get any triggers in this time.  BUT<br>2/9","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 14 17:00:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1503415664605814784","full_text":"Now's a fine time to revisit the weird TIMING of the Kamiokande-II neutrino burst.  Here's the classic plot, annotated by Yuichi Oyama.  A thread: <br>1/9 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1503415664605814784-FN00lFLXsAoO4wK.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1503415664605814784-FN00lFLXsAoO4wK.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"18","retweet_count":"5"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 14 16:01:28 +0000 2022","id_str":"1503400930473123847","full_text":"In his book \"The Extravagant Universe\", Bob Kirchner shared this story about one telegram and one phone call from @ast309 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1503400930473123847-FN0nLeFWUAMUcLR.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1503400930473123847-FN0nLeFWUAMUcLR.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"14","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 14 10:35:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1503318780167999493","full_text":"Visual magnitude measurement from Beresford in Adelaide, S. Australia: M 4.3","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Mar 13 22:00:18 +0000 2022","id_str":"1503128844995285003","full_text":"B magnitude measured in South Africa to be 5.7","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Mar 13 16:00:38 +0000 2022","id_str":"1503038331977883654","full_text":"It's March 13, 1987, and today's when @PhysRevLett got a hold of the IMB neutrino paper.   (It'll be printed back-to-back with the Kamiokande one in the April 6 issue.)","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Mar 13 13:05:37 +0000 2022","id_str":"1502994291051753474","full_text":"... unless the hypothetical reclusive Samoan aunt turns up, this is the end of the photometric story of those early hours.  A nondetect by Jones (look at that!), then McNaught/Garradd (below) then Zoltowski, then a gap, Shelton, Jones again, then EVERYONE. Extraordinary.<br>6/6 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1502994291051753474-FNu1VRfXoAohP5t.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1502994291051753474-FNu1VRfXoAohP5t.png\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1502994291051753474-FNu1VT-XwAMt6VN.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1502994291051753474-FNu1VT-XwAMt6VN.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Sun Mar 13 13:05:29 +0000 2022","id_str":"1502994255689752581","full_text":"... and a subsequent examination by McNaught of all the photographs taken this amateur failed to show any asteroid or eclipsing variable which might have identified the date.\"  The moral is obviously KEEP GOOD LOGS/NOTEBOOKS FOR CRYING OUT LOUD. To conclude: <br>5/6 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1502994255689752581-FNu1T7aXoAQyWRy.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1502994255689752581-FNu1T7aXoAQyWRy.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Mar 13 13:05:24 +0000 2022","id_str":"1502994232847519747","full_text":"... and in the latter case, the brightness of the supernova was so similar to that recorded the following night by McNaught that McNaught suspected the data was in error.  The amateur involved was unable to recollect any corroborative evidence as to the date ... <br>4/6 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1502994232847519747-FNu1SlMWYAgCIo3.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1502994232847519747-FNu1SlMWYAgCIo3.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Mar 13 13:05:18 +0000 2022","id_str":"1502994209439199237","full_text":"... uncovered photographs taken by Frank B Zoltkowski, based at Woomera, and another by an Adelaide amateur.  However, the epochs of the photographs were not accurately recorded ... <br>3/6 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul></ul></div>","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Mar 13 13:05:11 +0000 2022","id_str":"1502994179814834182","full_text":"I'll quote from West and McNaught's 1992 \"Earliest photometry of SN 1987A\" (A&amp;A 256, 447): \"Several photographers accidentally recorded the supernova on Feb 23; the LMC being a favourite target for astrophotographers in the southern hemisphere.  Tony Beresford in Adelaide ...<br>2/6","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Mar 13 13:05:06 +0000 2022","id_str":"1502994158256021509","full_text":"Today's IAUC has the FINAL example of a \"lucky\" accidental early data point: \"Feb 23.62, 6.11 +/- 0.15 (F. Zoltowski, Woomera, S. Australia, slightly-trailed 11-min exposure, 135-mm lens, hypered Konica 400 film)\".  THERE IS A WHOLE STORY and it has a MORAL: (thread)<br>1/6","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Mar 13 01:00:12 +0000 2022","id_str":"1502811732124868610","full_text":"It's March 12, 1987. Today's New Scientist makes a good (non-1987A) hate-read: The Eiffel Tower wants to celebrate its centennial with a \"orbiting ring of light\", basically Potemkin Starlink, and now I'm mad. (Cyg X-1 discoverer Paul Murdin, writing here, is mad too.) <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1502811732124868610-FNsPTm5VgAAKXXj.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1502811732124868610-FNsPTm5VgAAKXXj.png\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1502811732124868610-FNsPTjFVIAg0qQn.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1502811732124868610-FNsPTjFVIAg0qQn.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"13","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Sat Mar 12 16:40:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1502685859363147789","full_text":"According to Nick Suntzeff, 1987A has stopped rapid color evolution and appears to be in a plateau phase.  What do you think, plot-it-yourselfers?","favorite_count":"11","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Mar 12 15:00:24 +0000 2022","id_str":"1502660789639028743","full_text":"You see a lot of spectral data talking about \"P Cyg profiles\". That's a spectral line with both an emission and an absorption feature at different redshifts, characteristic of system with expanding shells or stellar winds.","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Sat Mar 12 13:00:38 +0000 2022","id_str":"1502630647990472704","full_text":"After interpreting photometry from Feb.24-Mar.2 R.M.Catchpole says it shows an expanding and cooling blackbody.","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Sat Mar 12 10:36:05 +0000 2022","id_str":"1502594269370060804","full_text":"They can launch payloads up to 2 tonnes. If interested, contact ... <br>(OK at this point the IAUC prints Steiner's phone number which I am not going to tweet because Times Have Changed.)","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Mar 12 10:36:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1502594247907758087","full_text":"Jo√£o E. Steiner of Sao Jose dos<br>Campos writes to the IAUC offering his balloon launching facility for anyone who wants to observe SN1987A from a balloon from Brazil!<br>1/2","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 11 23:00:22 +0000 2022","id_str":"1502419187196735490","full_text":"B magnitude measured in South Africa to be 5.6","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 11 16:00:51 +0000 2022","id_str":"1502313612848861184","full_text":"If SN1987 had made radioactive argon out of the chlorine in Ray Davis's Homestake experiment, it would have been extracted in a March 4th elution, and some of it would have decayed in the March 4--10 counting period.  They saw no such decays, today's IAUC reports.","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 11 15:00:10 +0000 2022","id_str":"1502298341920681984","full_text":"... of measuring neutrino interactions with good precision. The normal event rate in the detector from neutrinos produced by cosmic rays in the upper atmosphere is 1/day.  The signal is coincident with a similar observation reported by the Kamioka collaboration (IAUC 4338).\"<br>3/3","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 11 15:00:05 +0000 2022","id_str":"1502298320370286595","full_text":"Eight events were recorded in a 6-s interval, five of them during the first 2 s.  The events are consistent with neutrino interactions of energies &lt; 50 MeV. The IMB imaging water Cerenkov detector has an effective mass of 4000 tonnes and is capable ... <br>2/3","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 11 15:00:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1502298298664853518","full_text":"It's March 11, 1987, and the today's IAUC (4340) has the official IMB announcement: \"A signal was observed in data from a nucleon decay detector near Cleveland, Ohio (long. -81.3, lat. +41.7), on Feb. 23d07h35m41s.4 UT. <br>1/3","favorite_count":"13","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 11 11:05:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1502239164040888322","full_text":"R.H. McNaught measures magnitude from Coonabarabran, N.S.W.: M 4.3","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 11 10:50:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1502235392707534851","full_text":"T. Beresford makes a visual magnitude estimate in Adelaide, S. Australia: M 4.1","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 10 23:00:23 +0000 2022","id_str":"1502056804540461075","full_text":"B magnitude was measured in South Africa: M 5.6","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 10 17:00:52 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501966327560421376","full_text":"It's March 10, 1987.  Today is when @PhysRevLett records *receiving* the Kamiokande neutrino paper.   I wonder if anyone knows what the refereeing process looked like.  @RobertGaristo?","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 10 15:05:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501937176761667595","full_text":"And if you're saying \"now that you mention it my reclusive Samoan great-aunt Maria photographed the LMC three times a night for 15 years, never told a soul, then bequeathed her PLATE ARCHIVE and STROMGREN FILTER SET to my cousin in Auckland\", that's be fun","favorite_count":"23","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 10 15:00:48 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501936111345491973","full_text":"Suppose an accidental exposure involves a fast-ish 50mm lens, ISO 800 film, 1-second exposure, on a tripod?  That should pick up a magnitude 5 star pretty reliably, can it push to 6 or 6.5?  ANYWAY if you think you have such a photo ... email me!","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 10 15:00:10 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501935954130456583","full_text":"The first two events point back to the LMC within 18  +/- 18  and 15  +/- 27 deg.  No events were recorded around Feb. 23.12 UT, the time of the reported Mont Blanc detection (IAUC 4332).\"<br><br>Note: \"2700 Hg cm-2\" is \"hectograms per cm^2\", a wacky measure of the rock shielding.<br>3/3","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 10 15:00:05 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501935932286533633","full_text":"in the 2140-tonne water Cerenkov imaging detector situated 2700 Hg cm-2 underground in Kamioka mine, Gifu.  The events were observed during an interval of 13 s on Feb. 23.316 UT.  The observed electron (positron) energy interval was from the 7.5 MeV threshold to 36 MeV ... <br>2/3","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 10 15:00:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501935910429937664","full_text":"It's March 10, 1987.  If you hadn't heard through the grapevine, you heard today through IAUC 4338: \"Kamiokande-II observed the neutrino (anti-neutrino) burst from SN 1987A. The signal consists of 11 neutrino (anti-neutrino)-produced electron (positron) events ...\"  <br>1/3","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 10 14:50:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501933403968446480","full_text":"In 2022, could there be *accidental* Feb. 23--24 LMC photos in a shoebox somewhere? Maybe your parents got a Leica M6 and tripod for their wedding and took it to Bora Bora. Astrophotography isn't the MOST likely honeymoon activity but that's none of my business.","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 10 14:45:03 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501932148294492165","full_text":"IAUC 4338: \"There is obviously much interest in prediscovery photographs that may have been taken of the supernova field between Feb. 23.1 and 23.4 UT, although it seems unlikely that there would have been many observers between Chile and New Zealand.\"","favorite_count":"12","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 09 21:00:21 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501664208257269761","full_text":"Note that this feed has talked a lot about IMB and Kamiokande (because I know those people and emailed them for stories.)  In solidarity with üá∫üá¶ I cannot email the Russians in search of amusing Baksan anecdotes. I'll post (soon) what I know from the sparse public records.<br>5/5","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 09 21:00:16 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501664186652401670","full_text":"I believe this is the first public description of the Baksan results---but news must have circulated such that they got invited. The conference proceedings will be their only 1987 publication; their paper won't go to referees until November (revisions: Feb 88, published: Apr 88)","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 09 21:00:11 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501664165039120388","full_text":"The new March 12 session will include Kajita (actually giving a solar neutrino talk too); Van de Velde; Oscar Saavedra from Mont Blanc; Evgeny Alexeyev from Baksan. The conference proceedings describe this as a \"four hour joint session\" with an audience of 200. <br>3/5","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 09 21:00:06 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501664143459377172","full_text":"Today, Jack Van de Velde---who had just, on March 5th, told an Orsay seminar audience about IMB's *nondetection*---asks V√¢n if he might make an announcement.  He stands up and reveals the Kamioka and IMB detections. SENSATION. Van cooks up a whole 1987A session.<br>2/5","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 09 21:00:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501664121175040002","full_text":"March 9, 1987.  The Rencontres de Moriond are a longstanding particle-physics conference, whose 22nd event (March 8-15, Les Arcs, France) is scheduled to talk about particle theory and cosmology and mostly not supernovae. Tr·∫ßn Thanh V√¢n is the organizer.   Thread:<br><br>1/5 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1501664121175040002-FNb7j38XEAUMd56.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1501664121175040002-FNb7j38XEAUMd56.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1501664121175040002-FNb7j4qXoAUj_ai.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1501664121175040002-FNb7j4qXoAUj_ai.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"11","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 09 14:02:32 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501559060377784320","full_text":"\"who has an x-ray telescope in 1987,\" you ask?  We haven't introduced them yet but the answer is Japan's Ginga (aka ASTRO-C).","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 09 13:01:06 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501543599741231110","full_text":"F. Makino notes there has been no significant x-ray flux detected since Feb. 25.","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 09 12:05:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501529490400464899","full_text":"T. Beresford in Adelaide, South Australia measures magnitude: M 4.2","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 09 10:50:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501510615340400642","full_text":"R.H. McNaught at Coonabarabran, N.S.W. measures magnitude: M 4.4","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 09 10:40:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501508097885540356","full_text":"D. Seargent at The Entrance, N.S.W. measures the magnitude: M 4.2","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 08 21:00:21 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501301820689428483","full_text":"Does IRAF make you feel<br>a) nostalgia for 1987<br>b) nostalgia for 2014<br>c) nostalgia for dropping IRAF cold turkey when astropy 1.0.1 came out<br>d) what's IRAF? <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1501301820689428483-FNWyDMhWUAUa8TZ.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1501301820689428483-FNWyDMhWUAUa8TZ.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"12","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 08 19:10:45 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501274239202209799","full_text":"(maybe you said \"oh hey I'll follow this astro twitter feed, I love looking at beautiful astrophotography\".  this is the opposite of what you wanted. i am so sorry)","favorite_count":"10","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 08 19:00:28 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501271651748614151","full_text":"HEP software nostalgia yesterday, astro software nostalgia today: In March 1987, Peter Stetson first described DAOPHOT, a software tool for crowded-field photometry you may still be using in some form.<br><a href=\"https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1987PASP...99..191S/abstract\">https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1987PASP...99..191S/abstract</a> <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1501271651748614151-FNWWm_xXEAY0s08.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1501271651748614151-FNWWm_xXEAY0s08.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"10","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 08 14:02:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501196545143853061","full_text":"I don't have a Soundcloud so you should listen to St. Lenox, AKA Andrew Choi, singing \"Superkamiokande\", inspired by a visit to Homestake Lab.<br><br><a href=\"https://youtu.be/h82B027s22A\">https://youtu.be/h82B027s22A</a>","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 08 11:05:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501152001975107584","full_text":"G. Garradd measures a magnitude 4.4 in Tamworth, N.S.W.","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 08 01:01:40 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501000160620470272","full_text":"And that's how IMB discovered Supernova 1987A neutrinos.  Bob says he \"didn't sleep again until the paper was written and sent off maybe 36 hours later.\"  That paper is <a href=\"https://journals.aps.org/prl/abstract/10.1103/PhysRevLett.58.1494\">https://journals.aps.org/prl/abstract/10.1103/PhysRevLett.58.1494</a><br>18/18 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1501000160620470272-FNSfsPCXIAAsHG6.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1501000160620470272-FNSfsPCXIAAsHG6.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"26","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 08 01:01:34 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501000136201326592","full_text":"John told Bob to check the data for a burst NOT AT THE MONT BLANC TIME but LATER, at 7:35 UT.  \"I know,\" said Bob. \"We just found it.\" <br>17/18 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul></ul></div>","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 08 01:01:27 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501000108212695041","full_text":"John Learned has picked up a rumor that Kamiokande saw something. He phones Tokyo to winkle the not-yet-published burst time out of someone (Yoji Totsuka, I think). He calls to Hank Sobel at home to get Bob Svoboda's office phone number, then calls Bob.<br>16/18","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 08 01:01:22 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501000086540763137","full_text":"\"I called up Fred Reines (my boss at that time) and he came into the office along with Hank Sobel and others from Irvine.\"  BUT THAT'S NOT ALL there is something else happening simultaneously in Hawaii.<br>15/18 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1501000086540763137-FNSfn_6XoAM1K4I.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1501000086540763137-FNSfn_6XoAM1K4I.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1501000086540763137-FNSfn_9XEAUBymt.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1501000086540763137-FNSfn_9XEAUBymt.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"10","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 08 01:01:17 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501000063589523462","full_text":"Back to Prof. Svoboda: \"The difference with the 7:35 bump was that when I scanned the events on the display it was immediately obvious they were neutrino events.\" <br>14/18 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1501000063589523462-FNSfmokXEAMYXM1.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1501000063589523462-FNSfmokXEAMYXM1.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1501000063589523462-FNSfmojXEAAB8vK.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1501000063589523462-FNSfmojXEAAB8vK.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 08 01:01:11 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501000039799349253","full_text":"Here is a 3D wireframe view of the detector, with marks wherever a PMT has triggered.  The color coding shows the hit time; this visualization trick, invented by IMB, quickly became (and remains) a world standard. <br>13/18 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1501000039799349253-FNSflRhXoAcmFlq.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1501000039799349253-FNSflRhXoAcmFlq.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1501000039799349253-FNSflRdWQAIMl27.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1501000039799349253-FNSflRdWQAIMl27.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 08 01:01:05 +0000 2022","id_str":"1501000016533536771","full_text":"Are those events neutrinos?  Remember that Bob has not yet programmed the real neutrino-event-recognition \"passes\" in software.  But remember that the HUMAN BRAIN is a pattern-recognition engine better than any 1987 computer. Bob fires up IMB's pioneering EVENT DISPLAY.<br>12/18 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1501000016533536771-FNSfj4sXsAQjmIO.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1501000016533536771-FNSfj4sXsAQjmIO.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1501000016533536771-FNSfj4mXIAAGGjn.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1501000016533536771-FNSfj4mXIAAGGjn.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 08 01:00:59 +0000 2022","id_str":"1500999989912342534","full_text":"(The funny thing is this ASCII-formatted histogram is not some custom IMB software---it's a standard output of the PAW/HBOOK analysis software toolkit written at CERN.  Your middle-aged 2022 host still has printed manuals.) <br>11/18 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1500999989912342534-FNSfiIBXoAMLqB0.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1500999989912342534-FNSfiIBXoAMLqB0.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1500999989912342534-FNSfiH_XEAMlQKQ.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1500999989912342534-FNSfiH_XEAMlQKQ.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"10","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 08 01:00:52 +0000 2022","id_str":"1500999962691313668","full_text":"The x-axis represents time, with 7:30AM UTC on the left and 7:40AMUTC on the right.  The y-axis is the number of raw counts per six-second slice.  (Compare to the famous Kamiokande printout, which is an ASCII scatter plot, not an ASCII histogram.)<br>10/18","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 08 01:00:47 +0000 2022","id_str":"1500999938360160259","full_text":"\"I simply plotted the raw trigger rate of low-energy events out of this first pass and looked for bumps, of which there were many.\" HERE IS THAT PRINTOUT, which Bob has framed on the wall of his office at UC Davis. <br>9/18 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1500999938360160259-FNSffJhXoAIdhN7.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1500999938360160259-FNSffJhXoAIdhN7.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"13","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 08 01:00:40 +0000 2022","id_str":"1500999911571169281","full_text":"\"There were three data passes necessary, but I had only finished re-writing the first one, which brought us down to about 5 events per minute, from 3 per second.\"<br>8/18","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 08 01:00:35 +0000 2022","id_str":"1500999890008170502","full_text":"\"We had just replaced all the 5inch PMTs in IMB with 8inch PMTs, and I was re-writing the analysis code to get us from the 3 events/second muons to the few events/day atmospheric neutrino signal.\"<br>7/18","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 08 01:00:30 +0000 2022","id_str":"1500999868373946368","full_text":"Bob Svoboda, then a postdoc at UC Irvine, asked Bud Bratton at CSU for copies of the tapes.  The good period (before Feb 23.2) and the bad (after).  Today, Bob is looking at the \"bad\" data for the first time, and the first to see it's NOT THAT BAD. I'll quote him:<br>6/18","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 08 01:00:25 +0000 2022","id_str":"1500999845896724481","full_text":"They also had the later data, after the midnight PMT trip, but why bother with that junk when Mont Blanc already supplied the timestamp?  So they STOPPED.<br>5/18 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul></ul></div>","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 08 01:00:17 +0000 2022","id_str":"1500999812669452288","full_text":"The Michigan IMB group was excited when IAU Circular 4323 dropped Feb 28.  Mont Blanc reported that burst of neutrinos at Feb. 23.124 UT---10PM on the 22nd---a period of GOOD DATA on from BEFORE THE TRIP. They had the tapes, so they checked, and found NOTHING.<br>4/18","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 08 01:00:12 +0000 2022","id_str":"1500999791102287878","full_text":"The IMB data acquisition system kept on cranking away, writing data to disk.  Good data prior to midnight, slightly crappy data after midnight.  A few days later these data tapes, good and bad, got shipped to Michigan for analysis.<br>3/18","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 08 01:00:06 +0000 2022","id_str":"1500999769543565312","full_text":"This story ACTUALLY starts Feb 22nd, when an electric grid flicker at the Morton Salt Mine actually tripped one of IMB's four high-voltage power supplies.  Nearly midnight I think (UT Feb 23.2).  It took a quarter of the PMTs offline.<br>2/18","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 08 01:00:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1500999747699621890","full_text":"You're probably wondering \"Why hasn't IMB analyzed their data yet it's MARCH 7 1987 for crying out loud\".  Today I can tell you the NEVER BEFORE PUBLISHED STORY of the IMB data.  A THREAD <br>1/18 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1500999747699621890-FNSfUKNXIAcYVPH.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1500999747699621890-FNSfUKNXIAcYVPH.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"54","retweet_count":"16"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 07 19:03:14 +0000 2022","id_str":"1500909961169276931","full_text":"(thanks to Cleveland State University Michael Schwartz Library for the photo)","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 07 19:00:36 +0000 2022","id_str":"1500909296648953865","full_text":"Hello, Cleveland! Clyde \"Bud\" Bratton (@CLE_State) is the only IMB'er from a non-Ph.D. department. He shepherds the friendly relationship between IMB and Morton Salt (management, miners); he is, relevantly, the one you call if you want a data tape copied and shipped to you. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1500909296648953865-FNRNDODWQAYDw7G.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1500909296648953865-FNRNDODWQAYDw7G.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 07 17:01:08 +0000 2022","id_str":"1500879233199001602","full_text":"There is news about the IMB Experiment coming tonight.  By the way, do you know who built much of IMB's electronics, as a Harvard physics grad student (Ph.D. 1983)?  US Congressman Bill Foster!  @Foster4Congress","favorite_count":"15","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 07 15:00:51 +0000 2022","id_str":"1500848963045445637","full_text":"Science News, vol. 131, #10, page 148.  (Page 148? Is that the best you can do?) <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1500848963045445637-FNQWLYmXEAIcefU.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1500848963045445637-FNQWLYmXEAIcefU.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"11","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 07 14:55:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1500847496934961157","full_text":"G. Garradd measures the magnitude in Tamworth, N.S.W. to be M 4.4","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 07 13:01:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1500818810483494915","full_text":"It's March 7, 1987. In IAUC 4334, Miriani Pasoriza and Thaisa Storlhi-Bergmann (U. Porto Alegre) report on seven nights of Balmer line blueshifts measured at the CTIO 1-m and a spectrograph called \"2D-Frutti\" (!).  They say it's behaving like Supernova 1979C, a Type II. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1500818810483494915-FNP6wQxXEAY-RJJ.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1500818810483494915-FNP6wQxXEAY-RJJ.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1500818810483494915-FNP6wSCXIAMAJS_.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1500818810483494915-FNP6wSCXIAMAJS_.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1500818810483494915-FNP6wQUXIAIvHZ0.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1500818810483494915-FNP6wQUXIAIvHZ0.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"16","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Mar 06 15:00:06 +0000 2022","id_str":"1500486384150319107","full_text":"... where Larry Taylor, a diving safety coordinator for the University of Michigan---presumably more accustomed to working with marine biologists---narrates a repair expedition into the IMB water tank. <br>2/2","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Mar 06 15:00:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1500486361794686983","full_text":"Now's a good time to revisit the Irvine-Michigan-Brookhaven (IMB) experiment. One of my favorite IMB sources is this <a href=\"http://www-personal.umich.edu/~lpt/erie.htm\">http://www-personal.umich.edu/~lpt/erie.htm</a>: a 1989 article in Skin Diver Magazine (!) <br>1/2 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1500486361794686983-FNLMZOJWYAUTiAP.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1500486361794686983-FNLMZOJWYAUTiAP.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"10","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Sun Mar 06 14:00:20 +0000 2022","id_str":"1500471343355252737","full_text":"It's March 6, 1987.  At the University of Tokyo, the Kamiokande team has finished analyzing the complete Jan 9--Feb 25 dataset and, in parallel, writing it up. They're convinced they saw real supernova neutrinos on Feb 24.   The paper is submitted today.  <a href=\"https://journals.aps.org/prl/abstract/10.1103/PhysRevLett.58.1490\">https://journals.aps.org/prl/abstract/10.1103/PhysRevLett.58.1490</a> <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1500471343355252737-FNK-vCqWUAEt4pL.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1500471343355252737-FNK-vCqWUAEt4pL.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1500471343355252737-FNK-vDdXwAE7I1S.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1500471343355252737-FNK-vDdXwAE7I1S.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"27","retweet_count":"5"},{"created_at":"Sun Mar 06 10:40:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1500420936666865669","full_text":"G. Garradd measures magnitude in Tamworth, N.S.W.: M 4.4","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Mar 05 16:25:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1500145367920295943","full_text":"McNaught and Daw take another provisional magnitude measurement at Siding Spring: V = 4.39, B-V = +1.13, U-B = +1.38.","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Mar 05 12:40:04 +0000 2022","id_str":"1500088756967198723","full_text":"R.H. McNaught and J. Dawe measure provisional magnitudes at Siding Spring: V = 4.36, B-V = +1.15, U-B = +1.48.","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 04 23:30:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499889939529490436","full_text":"We'll have a steady diet of B magnitudes for you thanks to the @SAAO 1.9m at Cape Town (a twin of the Mt Stromlo 74\") via Menzies et al 1987MNRAS.227P..39M<br><br>Tonight we have: B=5.4 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1499889939529490436-FNCt83HXwAc0XjJ.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1499889939529490436-FNCt83HXwAc0XjJ.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 04 21:00:27 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499852293012869128","full_text":"Even if all exploding stars were the same (they're not) their detailed spectral/temperature/line evolution can be different because of these environmental effects.  So that's why March 4, 1987 feels like A Week Of Weird Spectral Line Diagnostics. <br>6/6","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 04 21:00:22 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499852271257071618","full_text":"Absorption lines tell you about cooler gas BETWEEN you and the emitter.  Some of that is random Milky Way/LMC material.  Some of it is older ejecta (winds, etc.) from Sk -69 202.  Some of it is the (cooler) outer layers of the supernova. <br>5/6","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 04 21:00:16 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499852249736040455","full_text":"Brightness changes tell you about the current size the fireball's surface.<br>Color changes tell you about its temperature.<br>Emission lines pick out a particular slice of the fireball at just the right temperature/density and give you chemistry information.<br>Absorption?  ugh: <br>4/6","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 04 21:00:11 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499852228231897092","full_text":"but then material from deeper in the star becomes visible, whether because the wrecked photosphere thins out to transparency or because it's mixing with ejecta coming up from below.   <br>3/6","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 04 21:00:06 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499852206723510285","full_text":"A star is basically a layered object like an onion.   During a star's life the only layer you see is the outermost opaque skin, the photosphere.  When it explodes, the first light you see is just the old photosphere, rapidly inflating<br>2/6","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 04 21:00:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499852183726141443","full_text":"We will not attempt to explain supernova classification (Type I, Type II, etc.) using the 1987-vintage infographics.  Let's jump ahead to 2000 when you can learn everything from these self-explanatory figures like this (Cappellaro and Turatto).  Short thread: <br>1/6 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1499852183726141443-FNCLnI1WUAAEmky.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1499852183726141443-FNCLnI1WUAAEmky.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"37","retweet_count":"7"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 04 20:15:03 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499840867422674950","full_text":"IAUC 4330 has a long report from the IAU team on (a) the continued, but slowing, UV dimming (0.2 mag/hr) (b) similarity to archival spectra of SN1983N (a type 1b).","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 04 18:00:05 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499806903450451971","full_text":"They will get only FOUR observations done before Saturn moves out of the range that let them navigate.   (I don't know if they tried to use their x-ray instrument yet; if they did, SN1987A is not emitting x-rays yet.) <br>2/2","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 04 18:00:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499806881459671045","full_text":"March 4, 1987. Time to meet the Franco-Soviet UV/x-ray observatory ASTRON, in orbit since 1983.  The LMC, it turns out, is somehow (?) outside the satellite's bright-star-based orientation-determining system.  They had to reprogram it to use Saturn.  Today: it works!<br>1/2","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 04 17:15:04 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499795572848422917","full_text":"Shelton and B. Madore report evolution of U-B and B-V diagrams follows that of SN1959D, a type II supernova, but they think 1987A must be about five times smaller than 1959D.","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Apr 20 22:00:55 +0000 2022","id_str":"1516899742130782208","full_text":"B magnitude of 4.8 was measured in South Africa","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Apr 20 16:05:31 +0000 2022","id_str":"1516810301118763013","full_text":"Looking forward, this is exciting because eventually the ENTIRE envelope will be transparent and we'll be seeing light from gases that were once deep, deep, deep inside the star.  /end <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1516810301118763013-FQzK7m3XIAoGcc1.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1516810301118763013-FQzK7m3XIAoGcc1.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"10","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Apr 20 16:05:25 +0000 2022","id_str":"1516810278201135116","full_text":"So the 1987A hydrogen is still expanding, but the *ionized* volume isn't quite keeping up---a \"recombination wave\" is starting to creep inwards and neutralize (and transparent-ify) an atmosphere around it.  You're seeing FRESH hot gas you have not seen before. 6/7","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Apr 20 16:05:20 +0000 2022","id_str":"1516810256625684480","full_text":"The hydrogen that was ionized/visible/photosphere-y on Feb 28 is now invisible---it's a transparent hydrogen atmosphere that you are looking THROUGH to see the NEW photosphere.  The new photosphere is some deeper gas that's still hot enough to be ionized. 5/7","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Apr 20 16:05:15 +0000 2022","id_str":"1516810235108900877","full_text":"But the \"surface\" isn't always there! Ionized hydrogen is opaque, great at emitting and absorbing light. NEUTRAL hydrogen is not---it's transparent!  As the photosphere cools, the outer layers are recombining! 4/7","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Apr 20 16:05:10 +0000 2022","id_str":"1516810213642412036","full_text":"it returned quickly to its equilibrium temperature---or whatever its equilibrium temperature would have been without that shock input---and then just got bigger and bigger. Expanding against the pull of gravity cooled it, but ... huge surface area = bright. 3/7","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Apr 20 16:05:05 +0000 2022","id_str":"1516810192079437825","full_text":"Actually the *very* early bright spike---the first days, when IUE saw all that UV---the supernova was bright because it was SUPER HOT.  You saw the shock-heating of the photosphere by the pressure wave coming out from the core collapse.  After that ... 2/7","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Apr 20 16:05:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1516810170440949765","full_text":"At day 55, SN 1987A is still brightening in visible light. Did you notice that it stopped getting redder? (That's why I am tweeting B-mags, people! For this!)  It's time to add some NEW PHYSICS.  What sets the supernova's brightness?  Thread: 1/7","favorite_count":"27","retweet_count":"6"},{"created_at":"Wed Apr 20 08:40:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1516698190669623301","full_text":"Seargent takes a measurement of magnitude from The Entrance, N.S.W.: M 3.2","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Apr 19 22:00:53 +0000 2022","id_str":"1516537342764494851","full_text":"B magnitude was measured in South Africa: M 4.9","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Apr 19 17:05:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1516462893440679942","full_text":"Campos measures the magnitude from Durban, R.S.A. to be M 3.3","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Apr 19 15:01:44 +0000 2022","id_str":"1516431860259336194","full_text":"It's 19th April 1987.  Ravi Sood (@UNSWCanberra ) and others got their gamma-ray telescope up on a balloon launched from Alice Springs but they did NOT see 1987A emitting ANYTHING in the 50--500 MeV range.","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Apr 18 09:10:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1515980963322511361","full_text":"McNaught measures the magnitude from Siding Spring to be M 3.2","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Apr 17 17:20:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1515741887583371272","full_text":"Campos measures magnitude from Durban, R.S.A.: M 3.3","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Apr 16 22:00:30 +0000 2022","id_str":"1515450084963631116","full_text":"B magnitude of 4.9 was measured in South Africa","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Apr 16 13:00:37 +0000 2022","id_str":"1515314217573830659","full_text":"@PhysicsCWRU ... H I Paschen &amp; Brackett lines, plus \"two prominent, unexpected features. One, a strong emission line near 1.9 mm, may be due to He I. The second, a deep, broad absorption in the 2.9-mm spectral region, may be diagnostic of dust containing low-temperature minerals.\"","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Apr 16 13:00:32 +0000 2022","id_str":"1515314195692236810","full_text":"@PhysicsCWRU ... today KAO is flying out of Christchurch with the University of Arizona Fourier-transform spectrometer and studying SN 1987A at wavelengths from 1.5--3¬µm.  Larson, Drapatz, Mumma, and Weaver report in IAUC 4370 ...","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Apr 16 13:00:26 +0000 2022","id_str":"1515314173965701126","full_text":"@PhysicsCWRU the beam exhibits various constructive/destructive interference patterns which affect the light intensity on the sensor (kept cold in a dewar).  The actual IR spectrum is the Fourier transform of the intensity scan data because of &lt;handwave handwave&gt;.  Anyway, today","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Apr 16 13:00:21 +0000 2022","id_str":"1515314151777783809","full_text":"Here is the spectrometer.  For each of two targets (!) it sends a beam into a Michaelson interferometer (shoutout to @PhysicsCWRU), then mechanically scans a mirror to adjust one spectrometer arm.  As the mirror moves, <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1515314151777783809-FQd6MNrXMA4CmFH.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1515314151777783809-FQd6MNrXMA4CmFH.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Sat Apr 16 13:00:15 +0000 2022","id_str":"1515314127056646147","full_text":"At 41000', it flies above almost all the atmosphere's water vapor and can observe in the mid- and far infrared.  Here are two diagrams of the telescope (see alt text for citations) showing some mechanical (vibration/pressure isolation!) and optical detail. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1515314127056646147-FQd6KtsXwAgZLXj.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1515314127056646147-FQd6KtsXwAgZLXj.png\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1515314127056646147-FQd6KuDWQAEpsnr.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1515314127056646147-FQd6KuDWQAEpsnr.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 04 16:35:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499785497421529091","full_text":"It's March 4, 1987.  Further narrowing down of the supernova's first appearance, Ian Shelton reports that his plate from Feb 23.059 at Las Campanas doesn't have it.","favorite_count":"11","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 04 13:45:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499742717433237507","full_text":"T. Beresford in Adelaide, S. Australia makes a visual magnitude estimate: M 4.4.","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 04 12:05:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499717551881863173","full_text":"G. Garradd in Tamworth, N.S.W. makes a visual magnitude estimate: M 4.4.","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 03 21:00:23 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499489889515098120","full_text":"<div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1499489889515098120-FM9CG8rXoAsZ_we.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1499489889515098120-FM9CG8rXoAsZ_we.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"90","retweet_count":"17"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 03 17:45:17 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499440789474185221","full_text":"The Large Area Scintillation Detector (LASD) a 140-ton liquid scintillator system sharing Davis's cavern since 1985. It never PUBLISHED anything on SN1987A, but Mike Cherry tells me via email that they searched for the burst and didn't find an excess.  YOU HEARD IT HERE FIRST","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 03 17:45:11 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499440767902883840","full_text":"(The latter---neutrinos change flavor---has been proven correct, and Davis's solar measurement won him a share of the Nobel Prize.  Yay!  BUT it couldn't do timed burst detection and didn't report a 1987A result AFAIK.)  As for the \"scintillator\" detector Bahcall mentioned?<br>3/4","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 03 17:45:06 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499440746436481030","full_text":"That 37Ar atom is radioactive and later decays---Davis was, astoundingly, able to collect these atoms and count their decays.  This showed that the Sun's neutrino output was \"wrong\"---either there are neutrinos missing or they're in the wrong \"flavor\" to react with 37Cl<br>2/4","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 03 17:45:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499440723007053837","full_text":"This feed has not previously mentioned the \"Davis Cl tank\" or the \"scintillators of the University of Pennsylvania\".  Davis's chlorine tank was designed to see solar neutrinos, which can cause the nuclear reaction nu + 37Cl --&gt; 37Ar + e.  <a href=\"https://www.sanfordlab.org/experiment/davis-experiment\">https://www.sanfordlab.org/experiment/davis-experiment</a> A THREAD: 1/4 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1499440723007053837-FM8VY9HWUAEb2Z5.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1499440723007053837-FM8VY9HWUAEb2Z5.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1499440723007053837-FM8VY6mXsAEJLzt.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1499440723007053837-FM8VY6mXsAEJLzt.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 03 17:30:20 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499437030060830726","full_text":"We also estimate about 3 events each in the scintillators of the University of Pennsylvania (Homestake Mine) and the Italian-Russian collaboration (Mont Blanc).  The results are sensitive to the effective temperature of the emitted neutrino spectrum.\"<br>5/5","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 03 17:30:15 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499437008476905481","full_text":"that about 50 electron recoils, with energies of about 10 MeV, are produced in the Kamiokande II water detector ...   <br>4/5","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 03 17:30:10 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499436986712707076","full_text":"Using neutrino fluxes from a model stellar collapse calculation of Wilson et al. and cross sections from Bahcall.  We estimate that only about one atom of Ar is produced in the Davis Cl tank but ...<br>3/5","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 03 17:30:05 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499436965183299588","full_text":"(Remember, at the time you're reading this ONLY the Mont Blanc claim is public!) \"We have calculated the event rate expected in terrestrial neutrino detectors from neutrinos produced in the formation of the neutron star in the LMC supernova. <br>2/5","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 03 17:30:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499436943343509504","full_text":"IAUC 4329. Neutrino theory just dropped.<br>\"John Bahcall, Arnon Dar and Tsvi Piran, Inst. for Advanced<br>Study, Princeton, communicate the following note, prepared IN ADVANCE OF the report of the neutrino detection in IAUC 4323:  \" <br>(a thread: 1/5","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 03 15:46:35 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499410918773428224","full_text":"@DrKeithSmith I think that is the first time I have described a European telescope using inches","favorite_count":"0","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 03 15:25:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499405494926065664","full_text":"One of the amazing things going on this week is realizing HOW MANY people have pre-discovery plates of the LMC just before the burst.   Today C. Madsen reports that a Feb. 23.042-23.056 UT color exposure of the LMC with a limiting magnitude of 12.","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 03 10:55:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499337546458877955","full_text":"(This 74\" has a sad ending: it'll be destroyed, along with all the other telescopes and the instrument lab on Mt Stromlo, in a 2003 wildfire.) <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1499337546458877955-FM63jbgWYAAPzvZ.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1499337546458877955-FM63jbgWYAAPzvZ.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"13","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 03 10:45:03 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499335034548989953","full_text":"March 3rd, 1987. Tuesday.  Paul Harding and Alex Rodgers are puzzled by the spectrum they took March I on Mt. Stromlo's 74\" telescope.  It resembles neither a Type I nor a Type II.   (Paul later joined @CWRUastro with the title of Observatory Manager, retiring in 2021.) <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1499335034548989953-FM61RMTXEAMBHI7.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1499335034548989953-FM61RMTXEAMBHI7.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1499335034548989953-FM61RMMWYAMY9FK.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1499335034548989953-FM61RMMWYAMY9FK.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"22","retweet_count":"5"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 02 21:00:21 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499127492166275074","full_text":"Sorry, we fell behind in supplying you with BLUE photometry.  Here are nightly B-V values (larger is redder) reported in tomorrow's IAUC 4328.  Plot 'em up! <br>Feb. 25: +0.05<br>Feb 26: +0.20<br>Feb 27: +0.38<br>Feb 28: +0.47<br>Mar 01: +0.68<br>Mar 02: +0.78","favorite_count":"11","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 02 19:58:57 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499112039662428160","full_text":"Today is ALSO the day that the Kamiokande team learns about the Mont Blanc claim.  They look back at data from the associated time; there are not dozens of extra events there.  It looks like an ordinary background-radioactivity-counting interval. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1499112039662428160-FM3qdKHXEAIC5Sc.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1499112039662428160-FM3qdKHXEAIC5Sc.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 02 19:00:11 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499097253411233792","full_text":"... \"We rushed again into data analysis.\"  (That's from 'The 20th anniversary of SN1987A' written up for the TAUP2007 conference: <a href=\"https://inspirehep.net/literature/802256\">https://inspirehep.net/literature/802256</a>) <br><br>NOTE: I cannot find a photo of Koshiba not smiling so here is one of Suzuki.<br>3/3 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1499097253411233792-FM3dAgQXIAkXeeQ.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1499097253411233792-FM3dAgQXIAkXeeQ.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 02 19:00:06 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499097230090940423","full_text":"Atsuko Suzuki recalls: \"Nakahata expected Prof. Koshiba‚Äôs smile for the discovery of historical event. On the contrary Prof. Koshiba did not smile and ordered Nakahata to analyze more data back to January 1 in order to make the burst sure for more significant confirmation.\"<br>2/3","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 02 19:00:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499097208091725828","full_text":"It's MONDAY, March 2, 1987, which means Masatoshi Koshiba is back at the office.  Nakahata goes to show him the burst discovery, plus the statistical analysis of 2.7 days of data showing a 12-event burst can't be a fluke.<br>1/3 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1499097208091725828-FM3c93zXwAUBHTi.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1499097208091725828-FM3c93zXwAUBHTi.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"18","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 02 18:01:33 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499082496348151809","full_text":"On one hand, we could go into poetic Carl Sagan mode about infinity and star-stuff. On the other hand DID YOU KNOW Kamiokande has wrapped 100-amp magnet coils around the whole cavern to cancel out Earth's 0.5 gauss geomagnetic field? (Big PMTs only work in low fields!)  Neato!","favorite_count":"25","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 02 15:35:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1499045625534504963","full_text":"Rangarajan, Jayakumar, Appakutty, &amp; Sheriff, at Vainu Bappu Obs. in Tamil Nadu, can see the LMC 10¬∞ above the horizon.  They're reporting V=4.5.  Note the PMT photometer!  I think the 40 cm was locally made under the direction of former IAU president MK Vainu Bappu. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1499045625534504963-FM2uDU7X0ActSGo.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1499045625534504963-FM2uDU7X0ActSGo.png\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1499045625534504963-FM2uDVSWUAg90_J.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1499045625534504963-FM2uDVSWUAg90_J.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"21","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 02 11:35:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498985225375866880","full_text":"Beresford makes a visual estimate of Magnitude 4.2.","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 01 19:15:03 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498738604553781253","full_text":"Campos makes a visual magnitude estimate: M 4.5.","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 01 17:01:30 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498704997076598785","full_text":"J. Menzies notes the spectrum has changed dramatically since Feb. 24, and is now more likely to be Type II based on very broad H alpha and beta emission lines","favorite_count":"10","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 01 16:30:35 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498697215111430152","full_text":"I have no idea what any of these lines are and judging by the IAUC reporting neither does anyone else","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 01 15:00:34 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498674564611596297","full_text":"Sunday, March 1 1987. What's International Ultraviolet Explorer up to today? 13 observations of SN1987A. (here are two.)  Six of Betelgeuse, for some reason? (Here, I'll throw in a Betelgeuse for you.) I think they're settling into a sustainable cadence for their 1987A coverage. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1498674564611596297-FMxckvGXEAgFv9J.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1498674564611596297-FMxckvGXEAgFv9J.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1498674564611596297-FMxckuRXoAAn_m_.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1498674564611596297-FMxckuRXoAAn_m_.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1498674564611596297-FMxckuDWUAcoYZk.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1498674564611596297-FMxckuDWUAcoYZk.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"11","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 01 11:20:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498619062259179520","full_text":"Beresford makes a visual magnitude estimate: M 4.2.","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 01 08:15:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498572505027653632","full_text":"G.L. White and D.F. Malin confirm Sanduleak -69 202 as progenitor star based on short exposure plates from Feb. 28.4 1987.","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 21:10:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498405152579104769","full_text":"Campos makes another visual magnitude estimate: M 4.4.","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 17:30:56 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498350014367739904","full_text":"(Koshiba will share the 2002 prize with Ray Davis, who detected neutrinos from the Sun   Neutrino-related work also won the 1988, 1995, and 2015 prizes; 1995's Fred Reines, former @CWRUPhysics department chair, will come up again soon.)  <br>11/11","favorite_count":"10","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 17:30:50 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498349991030665223","full_text":"And that's it.  The first detection of neutrinos from outside the Solar System; the dawn of what we will later call \"Multimessenger Astronomy\" and it will win Masatoshi Koshiba the 2002 Nobel.<br>10/11 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1498349991030665223-FMs1YHcWQAoyeBM.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1498349991030665223-FMs1YHcWQAoyeBM.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"27","retweet_count":"6"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 17:30:44 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498349967857102848","full_text":"Of the 12 events found today, the first two look like the electron (or positron) is flying directly AWAY from the LMC, possibly hinting that they were neutrino (not antineutrino) interactions.  The remaining 10 go every which way, as expected of antineutrinos.<br>9/11","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 17:30:39 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498349945488916486","full_text":"Recall that Kamiokande-II is a water tank with PMTs---giant single-photon sensors---staring in.  The Cherenkov radiation moves through the water, some of the photons hit the PMTs. Knowing which PMTs fired, and when, you can find (tiny arrow) where the source electron was <br>8/11 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1498349945488916486-FMs1Vd5XMAAsiYw.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1498349945488916486-FMs1Vd5XMAAsiYw.png\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1498349945488916486-FMs1VeIXoAQ4eNR.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1498349945488916486-FMs1VeIXoAQ4eNR.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"6"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 17:30:34 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498349921963020290","full_text":"In either case, the outcoming positron (or electron) is moving VERY FAST; electromagnetic properties of the WATER get tangled up by scrawny charged particle plowing through it, and it's forced to emit Cherenkov radiation---a sort of shock wave, but for photons.<br>7/11 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1498349921963020290-FMs1UF0XIAQRaiO.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1498349921963020290-FMs1UF0XIAQRaiO.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 17:30:28 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498349898848219139","full_text":"Here is how neutrinos can come to make these flashes: either the reaction antineutrino + proton --&gt; positron + neutron, or else neutrino + electron--&gt; neutrino + electron with an exchange of energy/momentum.<br>6/11","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 17:30:23 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498349876052115456","full_text":"What are these events? Instrumentally, whenever the detector's electronics see 17 different PMTs go off in 100 ns, they command a PDP-11 to save a list of those PMTs and their trigger times.  That's an event.  It means SOMETHING emitted a quick flash of light in the water. <br>5/11 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1498349876052115456-FMs1RWdWYAcJ6vJ.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1498349876052115456-FMs1RWdWYAcJ6vJ.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"4"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 17:30:17 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498349851632939011","full_text":"Nakahata is going to spend two more days zooming in on details of those events before even showing them to Koshiba.  He does not know that a bunch of impatient twitter followers want instant results.  (I can jump ahead and fill you in.)<br>4/11","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 17:30:11 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498349829122146313","full_text":"That's a ten-second window with TWELVE HIGH-ENERGY EVENTS.  Here's the non-ASCII version of that graph (from the forthcoming <a href=\"https://journals.aps.org/prd/abstract/10.1103/PhysRevD.38.448\">https://journals.aps.org/prd/abstract/10.1103/PhysRevD.38.448</a>) and a comparable background interval<br>3/11 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1498349829122146313-FMs1OpFXsAEwKB9.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1498349829122146313-FMs1OpFXsAEwKB9.png\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1498349829122146313-FMs1Op8XwAY4MVb.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1498349829122146313-FMs1Op8XwAY4MVb.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 17:30:06 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498349805105561603","full_text":"The key lines say (in time order)<br>1743.204  #        +      ++      +   +          +   +  +             +    <br>1743.304  #            + +         +     <br>for those of you who read Twitter in fixed width fonts<br>2/11","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 17:30:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498349782666035202","full_text":"Keiko Hirata just found a burst on the printout.<br><br>1/11 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1498349782666035202-FMs1L-CXEAEfMP1.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1498349782666035202-FMs1L-CXEAEfMP1.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1498349782666035202-FMs1L9cWUAANyf4.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1498349782666035202-FMs1L9cWUAANyf4.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"49","retweet_count":"12"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 16:20:43 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498332344725520391","full_text":"Did you know that astronomers---particularly in stars---use a lot of centimeter-gram-second units?  This is a fun fact that you should NOT use as a shibboleth to police \"real astronomy\" vs \"astrophysics\" disciplinary boundaries, he said, subtweeting cagily<br>9/9","favorite_count":"16","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 16:20:37 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498332322088861708","full_text":"(Was it passed around in samizdat? Nowadays you can get a godawful scan of it from OSTI at <a href=\"https://www.osti.gov/biblio/5894155-physical-processes-collapse-driven-supernova\">https://www.osti.gov/biblio/5894155-physical-processes-collapse-driven-supernova</a>.)  Here is one of Mayle's graphs of what material is where and when.   <br>8/9 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1498332322088861708-FMslTlBXwAc3x1-.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1498332322088861708-FMslTlBXwAc3x1-.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 16:20:32 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498332297321500672","full_text":"But \"expect neutrino emission\" is a 70's insight. How many? What energies? When? Ron Mayle's Ph.D. thesis, \"Physical Processes in Collapse Driven Supernova\" (Cal '85) is 1987's state-of-the-art.  Answers: lots; 10-30 MeV; a few seconds.  (Also the thesis acknowledges a cat.)<br>7/9 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1498332297321500672-FMslSOrX0AMygC3.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1498332297321500672-FMslSOrX0AMygC3.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"20","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 16:20:26 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498332273908797440","full_text":"As of 1987, everybody knows there's a supernova's worth of violent energy in here somewhere.  Nobody has QUITE figured out what---the shock at the bottom of the infall? the neutrino wind? Both?---is actually directing that energy outwards.<br>6/9 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1498332273908797440-FMslQ0UXEAolfck.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1498332273908797440-FMslQ0UXEAolfck.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 16:20:20 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498332249963610118","full_text":"The violent iron-vs-neutrons collision happens at around the same time that 10^58 neutrinos (both the neutronization products and neutrino-antineutrino pairs emitted by the hot plasma) are trying to get out.  <br>5/9","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 16:20:15 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498332228471898112","full_text":"Neutrons ARE fermions and they DO push each other apart eventually.  When they get dense enough to do so, a new outward force appears in a particularly violent way---interrupting the inward momentum of 10^30 kg of iron converging at 20% the speed of light.<br>4/9","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 16:20:10 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498332207022321665","full_text":"This is \"neutronization\". A whole pile of iron-and-electron-rich matter is freefalling inward, turning into a heavy-isotope, electron-depleted soup on the way. Every lost electron means an emitted neutrino.<br>3/9","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 16:20:05 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498332185522323456","full_text":"The reaction of an electron with a proton (e + p --&gt; n + neutrino) is endothermic---it cools the star a bit---but, worse, its end products ARE NOT in the pushing-each-other-apart business any more.<br>2/9","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 16:20:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498332163997118472","full_text":"While we're waiting: some physics!  A Type-II supernova happens when a star's core, unable to keep its density low by running fusion reactions, starts shrinking.  Shrinking means electrons (light fermions good at pushing each other apart) are forced close together.<br>1/9","favorite_count":"11","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 15:40:10 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498322140705300483","full_text":"I'll have more on Mont Blanc, and the general phenomenon that \"sometimes there are physics datasets that nobody quite trusts\", later. right now &lt;crossfade to 1987&gt; I don't want to get in the way of the ongoing Kamiokande-II scanning. 3/3","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 15:40:05 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498322119075237888","full_text":"The neutrino community (with a few exceptions) broadly interprets this as ordinary noise events, bunched at a random time by bad (but not implausibly bad) luck.  <br>2/3","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 15:40:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498322097604546561","full_text":"&lt;2022 voiceover&gt; Why do we thing the Mont Blanc events may be wrong?  Turns out they're the WRONG TIME and the WRONG FLUX.  Mont Blanc is claiming events at a time when the much-larger Kamiokande-II saw ... nothing unusual.<br>1/3","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 15:30:20 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498319667013771276","full_text":"NEAT: the LSD was attached to a line printer and ALWAYS printing out some monitoring data; that's how they're first to report.<br> <br>CAVEAT: these may not be real supernova events at all.  STAY TUNED /end","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 15:30:15 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498319645480206336","full_text":"\"in a collaboration between our Institute and G. Zatsepin's group at the Institute of Nuclear Studies in Moscow, consists of 90 tonnes of liquid scintillator in 72 counters shielded with 200 tonnes of iron slabs.\"  One neat thing and one caveat: <br><br>4/5","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 15:30:10 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498319623950942210","full_text":"\"The probability of a random occurrence with SN 1987A is 1 per 10^4 yr. The neutrino telescope, running since 1984 Oct. at 5000 meters water equivalent underground ... \"<br>3/5","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 15:30:05 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498319602455040001","full_text":"\"The signal consists of five pulses, above the 7-MeV energy threshold over an interval of 7 seconds.  This is in agreement, both in energy and duration, with predictions of collapsing iron-core standard models at 50 kpc. ... \" <br>2/5","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 15:30:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498319580925767681","full_text":"IAUC 4323 reports the first neutrino news, and it's a bombshell---OR IS IT?.  I quote: \"C. Castagnoli, Istituto di Cosmogeofisica, Turin, telexes: A signal was detected on Feb. 23.124 UT at the Mont Blanc Neutrino Observatory ... \" (a thread 1/5)","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 15:10:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498314558951280647","full_text":"McNaught measures brightness: M 4.4","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 13:05:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498283100098465797","full_text":"Incidentally, check this out.  Once a day (I think?) Kamiokande-II has a two-minute gap in the data; they have to \"take pedestals\", which means adjusting analog-digital converter settings on all the PMTs. I promise it will not be a problem. I really do. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1498283100098465797-FMr4iiWWQAI6RId.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1498283100098465797-FMr4iiWWQAI6RId.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"11","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 13:00:19 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498281914385457153","full_text":"It's Feb 28, 1987. Let's check in with Keiko Hirata. She's paging through stacks of tractor-feed paper that look like this. Each line is a 10s time window, a \"+\" near the left edge means a low-energy event; here you see the constant hiss of low-energy radioactive backgrounds. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1498281914385457153-FMr3dfWXoA0bxOb.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1498281914385457153-FMr3dfWXoA0bxOb.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 12:20:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498271774366121990","full_text":"T. Beresford in Adelaide, South Astralia makes visual magnitude estimate: M 4.2.","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 10:50:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498249126059859970","full_text":"McNaught measures brightness: M 4.3","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 09:40:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498231508770955266","full_text":"Weekend? What weekend? Supernovae don't take weekends. (To be clear Feb. 28, 1987 was a Saturday and the first time an IAU Circular was published on the weekend) <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1498231508770955266-FMrJninXMAAyLGV.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1498231508770955266-FMrJninXMAAyLGV.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1498231508770955266-FMrJnjjWUAIfnkX.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1498231508770955266-FMrJnjjWUAIfnkX.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"14","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 28 08:15:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498210119053684736","full_text":"Y.H. Chu examines narrow-filter plates taken at CITO in 1983, and confirms the additional companion. Star 3 is reported to be mag 17.5 and \"not red\"","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Sun Feb 27 21:37:57 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498049790667640839","full_text":"a) guess who is cited as confirming it.  just guess<br>b) imagine Northern Hemisphere observers waiting for Virgo to rise and weeping bitter tears","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Feb 27 21:15:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498044024992718849","full_text":"It's Feb 27, 1987. If you just pulled up IAU Circular 4321 you learned of ... 1987's second supernova!  Supernova 1987B, regular old extragalactic M=15 found in a 2/24 (!) image of NGC5850 by prolific amateur Robert Evans. (His finds are listed on his telescope tube!) <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1498044024992718849-FMofGh5XIAQch8X.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1498044024992718849-FMofGh5XIAQch8X.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1498044024992718849-FMofGgDXoAIezLC.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1498044024992718849-FMofGgDXoAIezLC.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"20","retweet_count":"4"},{"created_at":"Sun Feb 27 18:45:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1498006274100895752","full_text":"J. Campos in Durban makes a visual magniude estimate: M 4.3.","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Sun Feb 27 18:15:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497998723720388609","full_text":"Researchers at Space Telescope Science Institute examines plates from 1974-75 and suggest a SECOND companion to Sanduleak -69 202.  It's not a binary, it's a triple!","favorite_count":"15","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Sun Feb 27 18:10:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497997467798982659","full_text":"Visual magnitude from McNaught at Siding Spring: M 4.3","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Sun Feb 27 16:44:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497975824460521472","full_text":"could have said \"working IN\" instead of \"working on\"","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Feb 27 16:06:39 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497966416452104198","full_text":"I will post this again later (thanks to Yuichi Oyama for sending it): This is all four (four!) of the Japanese Ph.D. students working on Kamiokande-II. Takaaki Kajita, Masato Takita, Nakahata, Oyama. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1497966416452104198-FMnYJavXoAsuTEh.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1497966416452104198-FMnYJavXoAsuTEh.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"21","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Sun Feb 27 15:55:19 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497963563578802180","full_text":"Why did I say \"2nd from right\"? <br>a) I uploaded the wrong photo<br>b) to clarify that I am not talking about any of the I-beams<br>c) all of the above","favorite_count":"16","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Feb 27 15:00:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497949647201095680","full_text":"Hours ago, while it was still Feb 27 in Tokyo, THE TAPES ARRIVED FROM KAMIOKA at the Institute for Cosmic Ray Research. Honestly you could have almost walked over by this time. Ph.D. student Masayuki Nakahata (2nd from right) gets the processing started immediately. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1497949647201095680-FMnJQ-UWUAARBNG.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1497949647201095680-FMnJQ-UWUAARBNG.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1497949647201095680-FMnJQ9aXsAAe9VB.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1497949647201095680-FMnJQ9aXsAAe9VB.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"27","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Sun Feb 27 14:25:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497940843281502216","full_text":"Visual magnitude from McNaught at Siding Spring: M 4.4","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Feb 27 10:50:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497886734809509894","full_text":"Evolution of the UV lightcurve is much faster than what we've seen in other Type I SNs. Is it because of the low luminosity?","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Sun Feb 27 10:45:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497885478640566272","full_text":"Visual magnitude from McNaught at Siding Spring: M 4.2","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Feb 26 19:06:54 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497649389476720651","full_text":"since they are not following this Twitter account they don't know WHEN the burst was.  10 data-seconds per line, 10 data-minutes per page.  You can print 24 hours of data onto 144 pages and start flipping through it ... if  Hirata can write the text-dataviz code TODAY. 3/3","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Sat Feb 26 19:06:53 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497649388382003205","full_text":"MS student Keiko Hirata is on the job. Her strategy:<br>a) step through the data in 10-second windows<br>b) find all the low-energy events in the window<br>c) convert the list into a string<br>d) hit 'print' ... but  2/3","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Sat Feb 26 19:06:53 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497649386897166346","full_text":"It's Feb 26, 1987.  Thursday.  At U. Tokyo they're waiting for the *&amp;#$^ data delivery truck to arrive.  They've never done a low-energy burst search before; they don't have burst-search analysis tools.  Step one: follow the advice below and start with DATAVIZ.  1/3 <a href=\"https://twitter.com/ProfAnnikaPeter/status/1369488032248782855\">https://twitter.com/ProfAnnikaPeter/status/1369488032248782855</a>","favorite_count":"16","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Sat Feb 26 19:00:33 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497647791212007427","full_text":"Visual magnitude estimate from McNaught: M 4.0.   An aside: I know there are a lot of these and they're not SUPER interesting individually unless you're Plotting Them All (see <a href=\"https://physics.case.edu/realtime1987a-supernova-activities/\">https://physics.case.edu/realtime1987a-supernova-activities/</a>), but I wanted to report lots of them to give a sense of how busy everyone is.","favorite_count":"10","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Sat Feb 26 16:30:07 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497609935525400588","full_text":"Visual magnitude estimate made by McNaught: M 4.1","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Feb 26 14:40:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497582234018238471","full_text":"The first radio observations are starting now: Sydney's \"Chris Cross\" at Fleurs, on its last legs, at 1.4 GHz and Molonglo Observatory Synthesis Telescope at 800 MHz.  (They'll have a report in IAUC 4321 in a few days.)  It's visible and brightening! <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1497582234018238471-FMh7GtZXoAgPCRZ.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1497582234018238471-FMh7GtZXoAgPCRZ.png\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1497582234018238471-FMh7GvSXIAMXmAl.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1497582234018238471-FMh7GvSXIAMXmAl.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"29","retweet_count":"4"},{"created_at":"Sat Feb 26 14:26:53 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497578922145370113","full_text":"When you read old IAU circulars, check out the contact info options in the header!  In 1987 there's a telex number (\"710-320-6842 Astrogram Cam\") and a phone number.   BITNET will appear in a few years I think. <a href=\"https://twitter.com/rich_s_holmes/status/1497571313845739520\">https://twitter.com/rich_s_holmes/status/1497571313845739520</a>","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Sat Feb 26 13:20:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497562094996279300","full_text":"Visual magnitude estimate from McNaught: M 4.1","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Feb 26 13:00:37 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497557212868272128","full_text":"Further observations from IUE now say its UV spectrum is typical of a Type I Supernova with peaks at 292.0, 277.5 and 186.4 nm","favorite_count":"10","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Sat Feb 26 12:15:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497545739685277700","full_text":"Astronomers move fast. Multiple confirmations of Sanduleak -69 202 as a binary star. R.M. West thinks that \"star 1\" of the two went supernova.","favorite_count":"11","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Feb 26 10:40:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497521831917629442","full_text":"Visual magnitude estimate from McNaught: M 4.4","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Feb 26 07:25:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497472758061711366","full_text":"J. Dachs, at European Southern Observatory, finds emission peaks near 643, 580, 480, and 428 nm increasing in strength, indicating it is Type II","favorite_count":"12","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Sat Feb 26 01:25:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497382160948473863","full_text":"IUE data shows short wave ultraviolet light already fading rapidly.","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 25 23:00:33 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497345805237329924","full_text":"Someone found a Cerro Tololo plate from Nov. 6 1974 good enough to confirm that Sanduleak -69 202 had a companion.","favorite_count":"16","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 25 21:44:16 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497326604229349376","full_text":"@ast309 Maybe calling for \"frequent sampling\" when Rob McNaught is on the job is like calling for \"frequent 3-pointers\" during a Warriors game","favorite_count":"11","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 25 21:25:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497321762589229059","full_text":"Wheeler and Kirshner predict: if it is a Type I SN it will brighten to mag -1 over next 2-3 weeks, if it is Type II it should brighten to mag +1","favorite_count":"10","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 25 21:25:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497321762132209664","full_text":"J Craig Wheeler (@ast309) and Bob Kirschner put out a plea for organized observations: broadband photometry and polarimetry. \"Frequent sampling is highly desirable.\"","favorite_count":"17","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 25 19:00:17 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497285339324559366","full_text":"The grad student had ALREADY sent the tapes off to Tokyo via the usual delivery service. A van load of data will arrive at the university ... on the 27th. (Dear reader, in the spirit of RealTime1987A, you, too, must now wait until the 27th ü§£) <br>4/4 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1497285339324559366-FMdtFNRXwAAuAYz.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1497285339324559366-FMdtFNRXwAAuAYz.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1497285339324559366-FMdtFOJX0AokKIm.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1497285339324559366-FMdtFOJX0AokKIm.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"23","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 25 19:00:12 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497285315425415171","full_text":"Here's Gene Beier. Sid sent the fax to his U. Tokyo office. <br> But Gene uses a late commute to avoid rush hour. By the time he gets in, everyone else has read it! They've phoned up to Kamioka to tell the on-shift student to ‚úá PROTECT ‚úá THE ‚úá DATA ‚úá TAPES.  Guess what? <br>3/4 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1497285315425415171-FMdtD0rXIAMs5o9.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1497285315425415171-FMdtD0rXIAMs5o9.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 25 19:00:06 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497285291484319753","full_text":"Sid got his start in particle physics and cosmology, but by 1987 he's spent a decade on supernova hydrodynamics and neutrino emissions. When he finds out about 1987A (from the IAUC?) he sends THIS FAX to his Penn colleague Gene Beier, currently in Tokyo. Keep reading! <br>2/4 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1497285291484319753-FMdtCc2XwAQS3bV.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1497285291484319753-FMdtCc2XwAQS3bV.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"11","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 25 19:00:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497285268092637198","full_text":"It's Feb 25, 1987.  Astronomer-to-astronomer networks have gotten word out among observers already.  Who got word to the neutrino physicists?  Will they finally check their data tapes??   Enter: UPenn's Sidney Bludman and A THREAD: <br>1/4 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1497285268092637198-FMdtBE2XsAI9343.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1497285268092637198-FMdtBE2XsAI9343.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"12","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 25 17:30:12 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497262668184498190","full_text":"Nicholas Sanduleak thinks his old images of Sanduleak -69 202 are elongated.  If that means it was a binary star, WHICH star exploded?  The blue supergiant, or its companion?  (If one star's image is still there, it's swamped by the dazzling supernova light.)","favorite_count":"13","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 25 16:50:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497252557940482051","full_text":"McNaught at Siding Spring measures brightness: M 4.4","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 25 16:20:44 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497245186388226053","full_text":"Thanks!  Dr. Stevance's post is a quick read if you just want the flavor of the business OR a slow read if you give each illustration the attention it deserves!   Plus it cites the 1987A-specific <a href=\"https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1991ApJ...375..264J/abstract\">https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1991ApJ...375..264J/abstract</a> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/JostMigenda/status/1497242360626962433\">https://twitter.com/JostMigenda/status/1497242360626962433</a>","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 25 15:40:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497234942773927943","full_text":"The first polarimetry has come in.  Your humble Twitter host is unable to write a 280-character post about the importance of supernova polarimetry. Is it too few characters?  Or too many?","favorite_count":"14","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 25 14:45:03 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497221107430080554","full_text":"McNaught at Siding Spring measures brightness: M 4.5","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 25 13:01:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497194922197278720","full_text":"Spectrum over 115-320nm from IUE not indicative of any type of supernova, I or II, previously observed.","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 25 12:05:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497180834834661383","full_text":"McNaught at Siding Spring measures brightness: M 4.2","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 25 12:01:33 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497179961995763717","full_text":"Rousseau and Morel, armed with accurate positions and archival data, think the progenitor WAS Sanduleak -69 202. Are they right?","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 25 11:05:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497165736413966342","full_text":"D. Herald, Canberra, finds precise position: R.A. = 5h35m50s.11, -69 17'58\".5 (equinox 1950.0).  Everyone's looking at pre-discovery plates, including Sanduleak's, trying to pin down the progenitor.","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 25 10:40:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497159443745812499","full_text":"McNaught at Siding Spring measures brightness: M 4.3","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 25 07:00:13 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497104129193394196","full_text":"The International Ultraviolet Explorer does not take UV images, only UV spectra. However, it has a tiny camera to help it point its spectrograph.  Tonight, it's using that camera to report M=4.8 to 5, and its fancy spectrograph to report a \"strong, featureless\" UV spectrum.","favorite_count":"21","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 25 06:15:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497092753213300736","full_text":"Ian Shelton and J Claria phone in more color data.","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 25 01:30:03 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497021037413904390","full_text":"Brian Marsden compiles the incoming telexes and phone messages into IAU Circular 4316. <a href=\"http://www.cbat.eps.harvard.edu/iauc/04300/04316.html\">http://www.cbat.eps.harvard.edu/iauc/04300/04316.html</a>","favorite_count":"12","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 25 01:00:35 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497013621158813704","full_text":"A. Davidson, R. Kimble, and M. Gregg have another spectrum.  Many  hydrogen absorption lines are BLUESHIFTED as though they are RUSHING TOWARDS US at 15000 km/s.   They think it's Type II.","favorite_count":"14","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 25 00:45:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1497009707323740163","full_text":"McNaught and Garradd (now spelled correctly!) at Siding Spring examine the previous night's plates. It was there! 2/23.443: Magnitude 6.0. They send a telex to the IAU.","favorite_count":"11","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 24 23:54:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496996876473847809","full_text":"While \"submit an article to a journal\" is how you communicate your carefully-polished results, astronomers have had rapid communications longer than any field I know of.   The history of the IAU \"telegrams\" (later \"circulars\") is told here: <a href=\"http://www.cbat.eps.harvard.edu/services/cbathist.html\">http://www.cbat.eps.harvard.edu/services/cbathist.html</a>","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 24 23:54:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496996874938683399","full_text":"OK, astro communications history time!  Anyone who hadn't heard about 1987A via phone-rumor-mill may have heard via IAU Circular #4316: <a href=\"http://www.cbat.eps.harvard.edu/iauc/04300/04316.html\">http://www.cbat.eps.harvard.edu/iauc/04300/04316.html</a>.  Did you get it?  Please share your story! 1/2","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 24 23:33:06 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496991606230114304","full_text":"This is a story I hadn't heard: Colin Henshaw of Harare says he caught SN1987A in his regular LMC astrophotography habit with ordinary camera and 50mm lens.  I found his writeup here (plates not scanned unfortunately):  <a href=\"https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1987QJRAS..28..533H/abstract\">https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1987QJRAS..28..533H/abstract</a> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/NGC3314/status/1496924978624839687\">https://twitter.com/NGC3314/status/1496924978624839687</a>","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 24 22:40:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496978251197124617","full_text":"J. Menzies, in South Africa, captures the first spectrum. There's a dip in the spectrum at 615nm, which is characteristic of a Type I supernova.","favorite_count":"18","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 24 19:00:17 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496922948917202945","full_text":"In retrospect, it's funny that Albert Jones' NZ news set things in motion across NZ, Australia, and South Africa BEFORE Duhalde and Shelton's news made it 20km down the ridge.<br>4/4","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 24 19:00:12 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496922927383650322","full_text":"Secondly, none of these big-telescopes instruments are built for such a bright source, so you have to dim the incoming light with neutral-density filters, and figure out how to take (and calibrate) really short exposures.<br>3/4","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 24 19:00:06 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496922904851890185","full_text":"The ESO 1-meter hastily swaps its visible-light camera for an infrared bolometer.  Infrared observing from the ground is complicated---you use a special \"chopping\" mirror to rapidly compare the target star to a blank sky field, they were under was unusual time pressure.<br>2/4 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1496922904851890185-FMYjcwCXMAEqHKY.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1496922904851890185-FMYjcwCXMAEqHKY.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 24 19:00:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496922880701091847","full_text":"It's 4:00 tea time on La Silla. Groggy astronomers are probably discussing the nice clear sky when a phone call comes in from Mark Phillips at Cerro Tololo. They're calling the new star \"Shelton 1987\".  Everyone swings into action under the direction of Lo Woltjer (left) <br>1/4 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1496922880701091847-FMYjbVOXIAIgqcl.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1496922880701091847-FMYjbVOXIAIgqcl.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"10","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 24 18:20:03 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496912823246630913","full_text":"If previous tweets make you say \"calm down Captain Overkill, you just measured the same thing 3x in a row\".  (a) what else are you gonna do up there?  go back to comets? (b) some variable stars do things REALLY fast (look at RS Ophiuchi for example) and you don't want to miss <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1496912823246630913-FMYaR7NWYAgpZxo.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1496912823246630913-FMYaR7NWYAgpZxo.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"18","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 24 18:15:04 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496911572807073792","full_text":"McNaught and Garadd at Siding Spring measure the brightness: Magnitude 4.4 again","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 24 17:20:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496897719755018243","full_text":"McNaught and Garadd at Siding Spring measure the brightness: Magnitude 4.5","favorite_count":"15","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 24 16:15:05 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496881376758583308","full_text":"McNaught and Garadd at Siding Spring measure the brightness: Magnitude 4.4","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 24 12:20:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496822220752097285","full_text":"McNaught and Garadd at Siding Spring measure the brightness to be magnitude 4.8","favorite_count":"12","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 24 11:55:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496815931355508738","full_text":"For my friends Plotting Your Own Light Curves (<a href=\"https://physics.case.edu/real-time-supernova/\">https://physics.case.edu/real-time-supernova/</a>): welcome! we'll be tweeting raw data for you *at the time of the observation*.  Here goes!<br>Moreno and Walker, Auckland Observatory, are first-off-the-mark with filters: V = 4.81, B-V = +0.085, U-B = -0.836","favorite_count":"16","retweet_count":"4"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 24 10:30:10 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496794576933494784","full_text":"Dr. Marsden then phoned back to Rob to congratulate him on the discovery, but Rob said he was not the discoverer.  It was discovered by someone in NZ, but did not know who it was.  Dr.  Marsden correctly guessed who it might be.\"  <br>3/3","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 24 10:30:05 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496794554955362305","full_text":"\"Rob McNaught then checked the photos he had taken and found the star was recorded on them. Rob then phoned Dr.  [Brian] Marsden to say he had a photo of it, but as Brian was already on the phone to Chile, Rob told the secretary.  <br>2/3","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 24 10:30:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496794532662419461","full_text":"Albert Jones tells a bit of the next story himself in a 2009 interview which I will quote from Mark Simonsen's blog here: <a href=\"http://simostronomy.blogspot.com/2009/11/albert-jones-interbiew.html\">http://simostronomy.blogspot.com/2009/11/albert-jones-interbiew.html</a>  <br>1/3","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 24 09:55:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496785731007950853","full_text":"The clouds pass and Jones gets another chance.  He estimates its magnitude at 6.5 - 7.   Immediately he gets on the phone again; Frank Bateson gets through to @SidingSpring; everyone there drops everything else and gets to work.","favorite_count":"16","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 24 08:35:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496765598474596354","full_text":"Jones gets on the phone to fellow amateur Frank Bateson, who begins calling observatories around New Zealand.","favorite_count":"15","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 24 08:00:14 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496756845301866497","full_text":"Albert Jones, a prolific amateur astronomer in New Zealand, is out with his homemade 12.5\".  He hasn't quite started on his plan to observe the Tarantula Nebula; he glances up to check whether an incoming cloud bank will put a stop to this. Just in the nick of time. WHAT TH‚òÅÔ∏è‚òÅÔ∏è‚òÅÔ∏è <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1496756845301866497-FMWMa1lWUAAFKWV.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1496756845301866497-FMWMa1lWUAAFKWV.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"76","retweet_count":"10"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 24 07:00:09 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496741721866379268","full_text":"Shelton goes to the Swope dome, and meets Barry Madore, Robert Jedzrejewski, Jaymie Matthews, and Duhalde.  How bright, he asks, hypothetically, could an ordinary nova in the LMC be?  He shows them his discovery.  Duhalde nods in agreement and says he'd already seen it.","favorite_count":"22","retweet_count":"4"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 24 06:35:06 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496735417882017797","full_text":"High winds force Shelton to stop observing.  Instead, he brings the last plate in develops it (left).  WHAT.  WHAT IS THAT.   (Reader, look between two tickmarks just up and right of the 'm')  He compares it to another image from the night before (right).  IT'S NEW. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1496735417882017797-FMV47lKX0AMII_u.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1496735417882017797-FMV47lKX0AMII_u.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1496735417882017797-FMV47kgXoAE3LDw.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1496735417882017797-FMV47kgXoAE3LDw.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"48","retweet_count":"7"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 24 05:05:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496712753112829953","full_text":"Oscar Duhalde, another Las Campanas staff member, is busy changing filters and guiding the 40-inch Henrietta Swope Telescope.  He steps outside and notices a bright naked-eye star in the LMC.  Does he say anything?  Get this: HE DOES NOT <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1496712753112829953-FMVkUVmWYAMB4Di.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1496712753112829953-FMVkUVmWYAMB4Di.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1496712753112829953-FMVkUV2XwAUCq59.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1496712753112829953-FMVkUV2XwAUCq59.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"42","retweet_count":"5"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 24 04:50:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496708970958016512","full_text":"Thanks to Marcos for finding a photo of THE ASTROGRAPH, or at least the middle 3/5ths of it! @Dunlap_Obs points us to <a href=\"http://www.astrouw.edu.pl/asas/gfx/asas3_view.gif\">http://www.astrouw.edu.pl/asas/gfx/asas3_view.gif</a> for a different, equally bizarrely framed 1/4th view <a href=\"https://twitter.com/jmsantander/status/1496691886773489664\">https://twitter.com/jmsantander/status/1496691886773489664</a>","favorite_count":"15","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 24 03:04:21 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496682382870687747","full_text":"(Your host is embarrassed to admit this, but I have searched and searched and I CANNOT find a PHOTO of the famous 10\" astrograph. NOTHING. I am hoping to find one in a book that Inter-Library Loan is bringing up from Cincinnati---which itself feels like authentic 1987.)","favorite_count":"26","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 24 02:30:03 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496673748040228865","full_text":"It's early Tuesday, Feb 24, 1987.  Ian Shelton, an observatory assistant on Las Campanas, has been testing out the 10-inch astrograph.  His test target tonight is the Large Magellanic Cloud.  He has just started a 3-hour exposure.","favorite_count":"95","retweet_count":"14"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 23 14:19:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496489774605127685","full_text":"@SNEWSNeutrino e) the early Mont Blanc events are ... controversial?  Widely distrusted?  If they're real it's hard to explain (a) why Kamiokande didn't see them too, much less (b) what they would mean about the supernova.  Look forward to some Carefully Worded Tweets later. 4/4","favorite_count":"15","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 23 14:18:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496489521898311689","full_text":"@SNEWSNeutrino d) The 7-second gap in Kamionkande-II is the topic of a fascinating and surprising 2021 preprint; I have this queued up for a later tweet 3/4","favorite_count":"13","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 23 14:17:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496489270323859460","full_text":"c) Post-1987 neutrino physicists are VERY EAGER to see the next supernova neutrinos RIGHT AWAY rather than writing them to tape.  The Supernova Early Warning System @SNEWSNeutrino is on the world's most patient 24/7 high alert.  2/4","favorite_count":"18","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 23 14:16:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496489018586025994","full_text":"a) I promise you'll find out more about these neutrinos Real 1987 Replay Mode at the time the neutrino physicists actually analyze them. <br>b) Figuring out WHETHER the IMB/Kamioka/Baksan events happened at the same time will be NONTRIVIAL. <br>1/4","favorite_count":"14","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 23 14:15:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496488767347208195","full_text":"It's Feb 23, 1987.  Any news from underground overnight, friends?  No? Collected some data? That's nice, we're proud of you. Let's hope you saw a proton decay! Say, what time is it? Don't you have a good clock down in this mine?  Some notes for later neutrino tweets: 1/3","favorite_count":"27","retweet_count":"5"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 23 11:40:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496449766737207296","full_text":"Here we go guys! McNaught and Garadd, Siding Spring Observatory, take a photographic plate of the Large Megellanic Cloud (LMC), but decide not to develop it.","favorite_count":"40","retweet_count":"4"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 23 07:40:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496389373616607235","full_text":"But seriously that's 24 neutrinos within 10 seconds.  Many of them are at high energy (10 to 40 MeV) unusual among the ordinary noise events in these machines.  But it's still Feb 23, 1987 and they're all sitting silently on data storage tapes. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul></ul></div>","favorite_count":"40","retweet_count":"10"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 23 07:35:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496388111563116544","full_text":"It's Feb 23, 1987. Eight events were just detected within two seconds at the Kamiokande-II neutrino detector in Japan; then the detector appears dead silent for seven second; then three more events.    Then back to normal.  SHHH NO ONE HAS NOTICED ANYTHING YET","favorite_count":"385","retweet_count":"46"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 23 07:35:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496388111437377541","full_text":"The Baksan experiment in Russia detected five events but STAY CALM EVERYONE maybe NOBODY WILL NOTICE","favorite_count":"35","retweet_count":"5"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 23 07:35:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496388111324098568","full_text":"SHUT THE FRONT DOOR The Irvine-Michigan-Brookhaven experiment in Fairport Harbor, Ohio detected eight events and DUTIFULLY SAVED THEM to TAPE without ALERTING ANYONE","favorite_count":"46","retweet_count":"6"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 23 02:45:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496315131445366787","full_text":"(No detector other than LSD sees anything at this time.  It may have just been a random blip.)","favorite_count":"23","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 23 02:40:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496313871707090953","full_text":"Five events were just detected within a few seconds at the LSD (Large Scintillator Detector) deep under Mont Blanc.","favorite_count":"81","retweet_count":"5"},{"created_at":"Tue Feb 22 16:00:53 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496153026175942661","full_text":"You can get a charming sense of life on Las Campanas from a charming series of articles <br><a href=\"https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1996JRASC..90....7H/abstract\">https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1996JRASC..90....7H/abstract</a><br><a href=\"https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1996JRASC..90...69M/abstract\">https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1996JRASC..90...69M/abstract</a><br><a href=\"https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1996JRASC..90..115M/abstract\">https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1996JRASC..90..115M/abstract</a><br><a href=\"https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1996JRASC..90..270F/abstract\">https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1996JRASC..90..270F/abstract</a><br>except please skip the 2nd one because I'm gonna tweet half of it","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Feb 22 15:00:34 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496137846859706384","full_text":"Las Campanas staff and observers used their Wordle-free hours to do things like publish a little mountaintop magazine.   Here's the inaugural (Jan 1986) cover.  Note: I looked up \"vinchuga\" so you don't have to. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1496137846859706384-FMNZcEPXwAwd3yy.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1496137846859706384-FMNZcEPXwAwd3yy.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"13","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Tue Feb 22 14:40:11 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496132717519556612","full_text":"Any astro twitter folks up there right now, 1987-ly speaking?  @apolitosb?","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Feb 22 14:30:06 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496130179722264585","full_text":"You can look north up-ridge from La Silla and see the sleepier Las Campanas Observatory.  In addition to its two Carnegie Institution telescope, LCO hosts a little University of Toronto station, but two years after a 30% NSERC funding cut, that's just limping along.","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Feb 22 14:00:39 +0000 2022","id_str":"1496122771419586575","full_text":"Good morning, folks!  It's Sunday, Feb 22, 1987.  On top of La Silla, the European Southern Observatory's bustling 14-telescope observing site, the 24-hour cafeteria looks something like this.  Some people waking up, some heading to bed, nobody playing Wordle on their phones. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1496122771419586575-FMNLu1vXEAEQShr.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1496122771419586575-FMNLu1vXEAEQShr.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"20","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 21 22:44:16 +0000 2022","id_str":"1495892151917596672","full_text":"(extremely nitpicky erratum: it's not Monday, it's Saturday)","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 21 14:04:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1495761225136984065","full_text":"While Kamiokande, BUST, and IMB will talk your ear off about proton decay and atmospheric neutrinos, LSD's first conference paper (ICRC 1985) says something interesting 3/3 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1495761225136984065-FMIC6G6WYAsTx66.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1495761225136984065-FMIC6G6WYAsTx66.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"17","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 21 14:02:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1495760720138584069","full_text":"In this lab is the Italo-Soviet Large Scintillator Detector (LSD).  Like BUST, it's modular: 90 tons of scintillator (and 100 tons of iron) in 72 modules stacked three deep. 2/3","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 21 14:00:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1495760218910822403","full_text":"It's Monday, Feb 21, 1987.  Deep under Mont Blanc there's a road tunnel---until 10 years ago , the world's longest---and a nice little lab has been excavated off to the side.  The vast bulk of Mont Blanc makes it one of the best-shielded labs on Earth. 1/3 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1495760218910822403-FMIB_jFXoAMLZCK.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1495760218910822403-FMIB_jFXoAMLZCK.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"37","retweet_count":"5"},{"created_at":"Sun Feb 20 19:05:52 +0000 2022","id_str":"1495474803037421578","full_text":"@rbarris wait a minute ... do you all know something i don't know","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Feb 20 17:10:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1495445652955930632","full_text":"This star is burning fuel so fast and so pointlessly you'd think it was a cryptocurrency startup","favorite_count":"293","retweet_count":"50"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 18 17:20:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1494723393479970819","full_text":"That's fine, right?  As long as SOMETHING is burning, its heat output can keep the core temperature nice and high and prevent the core from shrinking.  Turning silicon into iron and nickel?  It's not pretty but it gets the job done.","favorite_count":"35","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 18 17:15:05 +0000 2022","id_str":"1494722147884929029","full_text":"The new photonuclear reactions are injecting some fresh helium into a super-super hot environment that hasn't had ANY helium in it for a hundred million years.","favorite_count":"22","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 18 17:15:05 +0000 2022","id_str":"1494722147868188679","full_text":"And while a hot ball of silicon and sulfur can't really run fusion reactions, a hot ball of silicon, sulfur, and helium CAN.  and DOES.","favorite_count":"16","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 18 17:15:05 +0000 2022","id_str":"1494722147859771394","full_text":"Sanduleak -69 222 is now doing SILICON BURNING at 3.5 billion degrees kelvin.","favorite_count":"45","retweet_count":"8"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 18 17:10:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1494720879720288273","full_text":"Sk -96 202's temperature has risen to like 3 billion kelvin, and that's hot enough to knock alpha particles OUT of silicon nuclei.   We're getting silicon breaking up into sulfur and helium.","favorite_count":"18","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 18 17:05:03 +0000 2022","id_str":"1494719623702491147","full_text":"Folks, there is trouble in Sanduleak -69 202.  Big trouble.","favorite_count":"25","retweet_count":"8"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 18 14:06:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1494674562776190977","full_text":"It's great at detecting high-energy muons, which it can track as they pass from layer to layer.  But it reads out lots of data, including medium-energy events that deposit 20-30 MeV in a single module.  hmm I wonder if that will happen later","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 18 14:04:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1494674061733109761","full_text":"Whereas Kamiokande and IMB are big monolithic water tanks, BUST is modular. Each module is a 60-liter tank of scintillator with one PMT.  BUST is a three-story building with four layers of these tanks and a TON of #zillowgonewild potential.  0 br, 0 ba, 3180 detector modules <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1494674061733109761-FL4mI1_XEAEWzzi.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1494674061733109761-FL4mI1_XEAEWzzi.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"14","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 18 14:02:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1494673559515447308","full_text":"The Baksan Neutrino Observatory is a whole underground lab purpose-built beneath Mt. Andyrchi in the Caucasus. BUST is one of several neutrino experiments there.  The workers' village at its entrance is named \"Neutrino\" and the hotel name on this map is even better <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1494673559515447308-FL4lriEX0AgZlMb.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1494673559515447308-FL4lriEX0AgZlMb.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1494673559515447308-FL4lrltWUAUSBXS.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1494673559515447308-FL4lrltWUAUSBXS.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 18 14:00:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1494673055804702721","full_text":"It's Feb 18, 1987. Wednesday. Less than a month since Gorbachev first used the term –¥–µ–º–æ–∫—Ä–∞—Ç–∏–∑–∞—Ü–∏—è (democratization), but the tenth year of datataking for the Baksan Underground Scintillation Telescope (BUST) in the Caucasus. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1494673055804702721-FL4lOUqXMAIo17d.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1494673055804702721-FL4lOUqXMAIo17d.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"12","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 17 19:19:10 +0000 2022","id_str":"1494390986474065928","full_text":"There are many more TELESCOPES to introduce, but for the most part we'll talk about each one When It Comes Into The Story.","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 17 19:12:35 +0000 2022","id_str":"1494389329031942150","full_text":"TWO MORE neutrino experiments we need to introduce: Mont Blanc's Liquid Scintillation Detector (not gonna type the acronym, not here, nope), &amp; the Baksan Underground Scintillation telescope (BUST).  <br><br>Question: are any actual Mont Blanc or BUST collaborators on Twitter?","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 17 15:15:05 +0000 2022","id_str":"1494329560870973441","full_text":"I don't think the Curtis Schmidt telescope will have a CCD camera until 1993.","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 17 15:10:03 +0000 2022","id_str":"1494328297076912133","full_text":"In fact, wide-field-of-view Schmidt survey applications like Sanduleak's are the ones that will use photographic plates the longest the 1990s. It takes a LOT of expensive sensors to outperform one big cheap film plate.","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 17 15:05:05 +0000 2022","id_str":"1494327045060382737","full_text":"\"glass plates?\".  Sanduleak's survey predates the mid-70s invention of CCDs.  Here in 1987, most telescopes use CCDs but old-skool photography is still in everyday use.   (This will persist into the 1990s!  Look what the APPLAUSE archive is doing: <a href=\"http://ow.ly/3vrF50HNBVS\">http://ow.ly/3vrF50HNBVS</a>) <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1494327045060382737-FLzqh0-VEAEQvFy.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1494327045060382737-FLzqh0-VEAEQvFy.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 17 15:01:26 +0000 2022","id_str":"1494326126545563649","full_text":"Last bit about Sanduleak's 1970 survey.  The original glass plates from this survey are archived at @Astronomy_PARI in North Carolina, along with 100,000 other plates and films dating back to 1911.","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Sat Apr 16 13:00:09 +0000 2022","id_str":"1515314102108884997","full_text":"It's April 16, 1987---first 1987A-observing flight of the Kuiper Airborne Observatory!  KPO is a 91cm telescope that observes through an OPEN HATCH in a LOCKHEED C141 AIRLINER in the STRATOSPHERE which is worth a THREAD<br>1/3 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1515314102108884997-FQd6JXNWYAUiSue.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1515314102108884997-FQd6JXNWYAUiSue.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"26","retweet_count":"4"},{"created_at":"Sat Apr 16 10:05:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1515270029767548931","full_text":"McNaught takes a measuresment of magnitude from Siding Spring: M 3.3","favorite_count":"0","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Fri Apr 15 15:01:50 +0000 2022","id_str":"1514982336491888645","full_text":"Menzel's 1967 writeup of the Damon sky patrol is fun reading if you want a deep in-the-weeds survey of technical minutiae of midcentury glass plate astronomy.  My favorite part is the machine for putting calibration spots and metadata on each plate. <a href=\"https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1967phae.proj.2635I/abstract\">https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1967phae.proj.2635I/abstract</a> <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1514982336491888645-FQZMZ5xaAAEBi09.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1514982336491888645-FQZMZ5xaAAEBi09.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1514982336491888645-FQZMZJOacAcKLea.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1514982336491888645-FQZMZJOacAcKLea.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Apr 15 14:02:36 +0000 2022","id_str":"1514967430141038597","full_text":"The Harvard \"sky patrol\" was Edward Pickering's dedicated but haphazardly-instrumented (50 years, 119500 plates) sky survey.  Ralph Damon funded Donald Menzel's reboot: six identical wide-field (30¬∞!) cameras to cover three colors (blue, yellow, red) from both hemispheres. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1514967430141038597-FQY-2SvWQAECq-s.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1514967430141038597-FQY-2SvWQAECq-s.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Apr 15 13:01:53 +0000 2022","id_str":"1514952147942707200","full_text":"IAUC 4367:   M. L. Hazen, @CenterForAstro:  \"No major change in the brightness of Sk -69 202 was found in a search of the star's area on 502 Harvard blue patrol plates taken 1899-1953 ... on 59 plates of the Damon blue patrol series taken in 1971, 1978-79, and 1981-86\" <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1514952147942707200-FQYw82eX0AgYDDB.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1514952147942707200-FQYw82eX0AgYDDB.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Fri Apr 15 10:50:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1514918967223148546","full_text":"Beresford measures magnitude from Adelaide, S. Australia: M 3.4","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Apr 14 17:20:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1514654727648296960","full_text":"Campos measures magnitude from Durban, R.S.A: M 3.4","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Apr 14 10:50:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1514556578959175683","full_text":"Seargent measures a magnitude of M 3.3 from The Entrance, N.S.W.","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Apr 13 22:00:59 +0000 2022","id_str":"1514363043353960449","full_text":"B magnitude measured in South Africa to be 5.0","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Apr 13 16:02:58 +0000 2022","id_str":"1514272944222048256","full_text":"\"... on Mar. 3 ... the SN signal was located between the stellar spectra, about 2\".9 +/- 0\".2 from the northern stellar component.  We identify the northern component with star 2 and the southern component with star 3 and conclude that star 1, Sk -69 202, has disappeared.\" <div class=\"gallery\"><ul></ul></div>","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Apr 13 15:01:59 +0000 2022","id_str":"1514257598610087946","full_text":"\"The stellar spectra are fit extremely well by two point-sources separated by 4\".13 +/- 0\".35 ... this separation is in agreement with that expected for stars 2 and 3 (IAUC 4356) and inconsistent with the separation of either stars 1 and 2 or stars 1 and 3.\" <div class=\"gallery\"><ul></ul></div>","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Apr 13 14:02:33 +0000 2022","id_str":"1514242642053324804","full_text":"It's April 13, 1987, and today IAUC 4366 has the news you've been waiting for: reanalysis of the International Ultraviolet Explorer data, taking into account the past month's laborious archival-plate astrometry of both companions, reveals SANDULEAK -69 202  IS GONE AFTER ALL <div class=\"gallery\"><ul></ul></div>","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Apr 13 12:01:40 +0000 2022","id_str":"1514212219126435845","full_text":"E.L. Chupp (University of New Hampshire) reports no gamma-ray burst assocated with core collapse, but continues to monitor area in case","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Apr 13 11:05:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1514197967447928833","full_text":"Beresford measures magnitude from Adelaide, S. Australia to be M 3.4","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Apr 12 16:20:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1513914849906110464","full_text":"B. Gregory and J. Elias get infrared photometry and determine the suoernova has increased in 10-;m brightness by more than 1 magnitude in less than 1 month","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Apr 12 09:10:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1513806635239677957","full_text":"McNaught measures magnitude from Siding Spring: M 3.5","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Apr 11 22:00:52 +0000 2022","id_str":"1513638237633396737","full_text":"B magnitude was measured in South Africa: M 5.1","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Apr 11 17:00:57 +0000 2022","id_str":"1513562760478707714","full_text":"It's April 11, 1987.  Supernova 1987A is the 300th brightest thing in the sky; brighter than anything in Cancer or Pisces.  For comparison it looks a fair bit like Epsilon Tauri, which you can see yourself tonight.  <a href=\"https://astronomy.com/magazine/sky-this-month/2022/04/sky-this-month-april-2022\">https://astronomy.com/magazine/sky-this-month/2022/04/sky-this-month-april-2022</a> will help you find it. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1513562760478707714-FQFBTxrXwAs3TBL.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1513562760478707714-FQFBTxrXwAs3TBL.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Mon Apr 11 13:01:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1513502376191213570","full_text":"Meet the team! @RealTime1987A has been brought to you with the help of Ama Carney (CWRU BS '19), now a thermal engineer working on her PhD in aerospace engineering, and Adrian Lee, a Teacher Education and Physics major in the class of 2022. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1513502376191213570-FQEKY2GXMAMqhje.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1513502376191213570-FQEKY2GXMAMqhje.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1513502376191213570-FQEKYwVXsAcPvwn.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1513502376191213570-FQEKYwVXsAcPvwn.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"42","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Apr 11 09:40:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1513451797431701508","full_text":"Seargent measures magnitude from The Entrance, N.S.W.: M 3.4","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 16 21:38:43 +0000 2022","id_str":"1494063717285175301","full_text":"&lt;yawn&gt;","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 16 21:38:42 +0000 2022","id_str":"1494063716077162501","full_text":"......üí•......................................................................üêÅ..........................................","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 16 21:38:42 +0000 2022","id_str":"1494063714831536128","full_text":"...........üêÅ.......üêÅ.....................üêÅ..............................................................................","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 16 21:38:42 +0000 2022","id_str":"1494063713598410754","full_text":".........................üêÅ...üêÅ.................üêÅ..üêÅ.........................üêÅ...............üêÅ...........................","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 16 21:38:42 +0000 2022","id_str":"1494063712373657604","full_text":".......üí•.........üêÅ.....................................................................................................üêÅ","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 16 21:38:41 +0000 2022","id_str":"1494063711018831872","full_text":"....................................................................................................üêÅ...................","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 16 21:38:41 +0000 2022","id_str":"1494063709597040642","full_text":"Let's check in with what Kamioka-II is doing right now.  One character per second.<br>. = nothing <br>üêÅ = 6-10 MeV event<br>üòª = 10-20 MeV event<br>üí• = 20-30 MeV event<br>üéä = 30-40 MeV event<br>Here's a thread of typical two-minute runs:","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 16 16:53:49 +0000 2022","id_str":"1493992019659689985","full_text":"lookit all those cute lil' @HamamatsuPhoton R11410s all snuggled up close<br><br>Fun PMT fact: after IMB was shut down, its R1408 tubes were salvaged, and thousands are still being used today. Who's got some? SNO+? SuperK? <a href=\"https://twitter.com/XENONexperiment/status/1493929785801777152\">https://twitter.com/XENONexperiment/status/1493929785801777152</a>","favorite_count":"11","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 16 14:15:05 +0000 2022","id_str":"1493952073620246536","full_text":"Yesterday we were talking about Sanduleak's objective prism survey.  Did you know the Curtis Schmidt telescope is still operating at CTIO, now owned by @UMich and used for space debris monitoring?  <a href=\"https://lsa.umich.edu/astro/facilities/telescopes/curtis-schmidt.html\">https://lsa.umich.edu/astro/facilities/telescopes/curtis-schmidt.html</a> <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1493952073620246536-FLuVfmNXEAQ19Ab.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1493952073620246536-FLuVfmNXEAQ19Ab.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Feb 15 19:00:27 +0000 2022","id_str":"1493661501307207688","full_text":"Breaking down the name \"Sanduleak -69 202\": Sanduleak's spectroscopy let him usefully catalog this dot, which was present in earlier images, as a likely Magellanic Clouds object rather than a foreground star.  It's the 202nd object in his survey stripe at declination -69¬∞.","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Feb 15 18:05:03 +0000 2022","id_str":"1493647558228557824","full_text":"What is an \"objective prism survey\"?  It means you add a prism to a regular telescope so that different wavelengths of light smear out across the image.  Here's an example of a regular image (left) and an objective-prism image (right) from Hubble. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1493647558228557824-FLqAigCWQAcRvOf.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1493647558228557824-FLqAigCWQAcRvOf.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Tue Feb 15 18:00:34 +0000 2022","id_str":"1493646430053060611","full_text":"Let's talk a bit about where this star came from.  It was first named in \"A deep objective-prism survey for Large Magellanic Cloud members\" <a href=\"http://ow.ly/hoEJ50HVHSc\">http://ow.ly/hoEJ50HVHSc</a>","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Feb 15 17:10:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1493633712310964224","full_text":"Sanduleak was educated at the Case Institute of Technology (BS 1956, MS 1961, Ph.D. 1965) and was a staff scientist at our Warner and Swasey Observatory.","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Feb 15 17:05:06 +0000 2022","id_str":"1493632472319500289","full_text":"Here is Nicholas Sanduleak himself in 1965 at Cerro Tololo, one of several observatories he knew well.   He's not worried.   He is definitely not thinking about this star, if he even remembers cataloguing it. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1493632472319500289-FLpy0ZcX0AwMlXq.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1493632472319500289-FLpy0ZcX0AwMlXq.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Tue Feb 15 17:01:21 +0000 2022","id_str":"1493631528110366721","full_text":"You're probably anxious about the core temperature of Sanduleak -69 202. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1493631528110366721-FLpx9S6XMA0zlX4.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1493631528110366721-FLpx9S6XMA0zlX4.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"24","retweet_count":"3"},{"created_at":"Tue Feb 15 16:55:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1493629937458241543","full_text":"(ERRATUM: a previous tweet referred to \"Sanduleak -69 222\"; the correct identifer is -69 202).","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Feb 15 04:59:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1493449753769697280","full_text":"ERRATUM: it's -69 202, not -69 222.","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 14 19:13:21 +0000 2022","id_str":"1493302361107795969","full_text":"&lt;breaks fourth wall&gt;<br>I hope folks are enjoying these intro foreshadowing tweets. Actual Supernova 1987A will start lighting up your phone early on Feb 23.<br><br>Looking for Supernova 1987B? It's Feb 24, ok weirdo? It will not light up your phone.<br>&lt;wavy dissolve back to 1987&gt;","favorite_count":"34","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 14 14:30:27 +0000 2022","id_str":"1493231166241005571","full_text":"Anyway, after two years of radon-fighting engineering runs, Kamiokande-II started its solar neutrino data campaign LAST MONTH.  I bet this solar neutrino result will be the BIGGEST neutrino news of 1987-88!  üçø","favorite_count":"13","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 14 14:30:22 +0000 2022","id_str":"1493231144560693249","full_text":"Secondly, Kamiokande-II can tell what DIRECTION a neutrino came from---each neutrino interaction sends an electron in roughly the neutrino's direction. Neutrinos from the sun always send electrons in a particular anti-sun direction. Radioactive decays go every which way.","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 14 14:30:17 +0000 2022","id_str":"1493231122402189316","full_text":"Fortunately Kamiokande-II got the backgrounds down to like ONE event every FIVE SECONDS which is amazing.  If you are not in the field, it has hard to overstate what an achievement this is. üèÜ <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1493231122402189316-FLkFytvX0AAA4IO.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1493231122402189316-FLkFytvX0AAA4IO.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 14 14:30:11 +0000 2022","id_str":"1493231098758934528","full_text":"Solar neutrinos produce small flashes in a detector like this; the most-detectable ones are only 5-10 MeV.  The detector can only isolate THOSE puny events if they can prevent U, Th, and Rn from dissolving in the water and making similar-looking events when decaying. ‚ò¢Ô∏è","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 14 14:30:06 +0000 2022","id_str":"1493231076805857286","full_text":"1987 is going to be an exciting year for Kamiokande-II because they have JUST STARTED a serious attempt to be sensitive to solar neutrinos, a harder task than the proton-decay focus its predecessor KamiokaNDE or, say, IMB. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1493231076805857286-FLkFwE7XMAIGHJi.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1493231076805857286-FLkFwE7XMAIGHJi.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 14 14:30:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1493231053154267139","full_text":"It's Feb. 14, 1987. Saturday. Valentine's Day! A great time to say \"I üíñ Photomultiplier Tubes\" to the Kamiokande-II experiment.  Like IMB, Kamiokande is a tank of ultrapure water deep underground in the Mozumi Mine in Kida, Gifu, Japan. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1493231053154267139-FLkFuurWUAUa3X_.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1493231053154267139-FLkFuurWUAUa3X_.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1493231053154267139-FLkFut9XoAAZxwa.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1493231053154267139-FLkFut9XoAAZxwa.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"18","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Sun Feb 13 17:15:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1492910194204057604","full_text":"Right now, Sanduleak -69 222 is an extremely hot ball of silicon and sulfur.   For the past few months it has been fusing oxygen atoms to make silicon, but it's almost out of oxygen.","favorite_count":"112","retweet_count":"13"},{"created_at":"Sun Feb 13 17:15:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1492910193843265542","full_text":"Therefore the core is shrinking and getting hotter.  2 billion kelvin and rising.","favorite_count":"21","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Feb 13 17:10:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1492908934184714245","full_text":"Sanduleak -69 222 was one of about a thousand bright stars catalogued by Nick Sanduleak in 1970 using photographic plates from the Curtis Schmidt telescope on Cerro Tololo.","favorite_count":"11","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Feb 13 17:05:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1492907679282511881","full_text":"There is a blue supergiant star, Sanduleak -69 222, in the Large Magellanic Cloud.  Nobody knows much about it.","favorite_count":"22","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Feb 13 17:00:39 +0000 2022","id_str":"1492906576780345347","full_text":"It is February 13, 1987.   Friday.","favorite_count":"15","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 11 15:42:06 +0000 2022","id_str":"1492162031746793472","full_text":"The CTIO 4-m will be renamed in 1995 after Puerto Rican astronomer Victor Manuel Blanco, longtime professor at @CWRUastro (well, its predecessor Case Inst. Tech.) <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1492162031746793472-FLU4m1vXsAEBlLk.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1492162031746793472-FLU4m1vXsAEBlLk.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 11 15:42:05 +0000 2022","id_str":"1492162028701724677","full_text":"(Both of the mirror blanks shown above are for the Victor Blanco.  The AAT will later take the image on this account's profile page.)","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Feb 11 15:42:04 +0000 2022","id_str":"1492162026143199237","full_text":"It's Feb 11, 1987. Six months ago, Roger Angel filed a patent that would lead to 8-m telescope mirrors; today, the state of the art is 4m. Ohio's @OI_Glass cast four of those: CTIO 4-m (later named \"Victor Blanco\"), Anglo-Australian, CFHT and (coming soon) Herschel. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1492162026143199237-FLU467VXwAAt3Il.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1492162026143199237-FLU467VXwAAt3Il.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1492162026143199237-FLU5L1RWYAc0EDD.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1492162026143199237-FLU5L1RWYAc0EDD.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"13","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 10 18:01:32 +0000 2022","id_str":"1491834734124490772","full_text":"IUE has been around since 1978 but 1987 is a pretty exciting year for it because finally users can access its archival data via modem. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1491834734124490772-FLQPlgVVkAIP4Kw.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1491834734124490772-FLQPlgVVkAIP4Kw.png\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1491834734124490772-FLQPx0lUYB8bRKL.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1491834734124490772-FLQPx0lUYB8bRKL.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"28","retweet_count":"5"},{"created_at":"Thu Feb 10 17:51:54 +0000 2022","id_str":"1491832310622261252","full_text":"It's February 10, 1987.  The new \"Hubble Space Telescope\", its launch postponed due to Challenger, is on mothballs but probably in perfect focus, right? In the meantime we DO have an AWESOME space telescope in orbit.  Meet IUE, the International Ultraviolet Explorer. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1491832310622261252-FLQNlNAWYAU4Y2J.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1491832310622261252-FLQNlNAWYAU4Y2J.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"17","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 09 20:46:20 +0000 2022","id_str":"1491513821717880833","full_text":"stay tuned for my next exciting twitter feed, Real Time Poisson Randomly Generated Emoji Strings","favorite_count":"13","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 09 20:44:33 +0000 2022","id_str":"1491513370574417920","full_text":"Of course here in 1987 we can't print out emojis.  Our dot matrix printers have to make do with ASCII.  We lived closer to nature.  It was a simpler time.","favorite_count":"29","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 09 20:44:32 +0000 2022","id_str":"1491513368829517826","full_text":"üí•........üí•..........üí•..............üéä......üí•........üí•........üí•...........üéä................................üéä..............","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 09 20:44:32 +0000 2022","id_str":"1491513366891798529","full_text":".....üéä.......üéäüéä.......................................................................üí•...üéä...üí•..................üéä..üí•...","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 09 20:44:31 +0000 2022","id_str":"1491513364001935360","full_text":".üí•..................................................üéä.......üéä........................................üéä........üéä.üéä....üéäüí•.","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 09 20:44:31 +0000 2022","id_str":"1491513362185801729","full_text":"...üí•..................................üí•..........üí•.......üí•.............üí•................................................","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 09 20:44:30 +0000 2022","id_str":"1491513360524873729","full_text":"Imagine your data-readout computer printed one character per second, with a \".\" meaning nothing happened, a üí• meaning a 20-30 MeV event, and a üéä meaning a 30-40 MeV event, the following tweets are pretty typical two-minute readouts.","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 09 20:40:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1491512234178195465","full_text":"We haven't seen proton decay yet.  Smaller flashes---the debris of weird nuclear decays, triggered by a passing muon, long story TBH---are common.   These show up as 20-40 MeV events and they happen at a rate of 4 per minute all day every day.","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 09 20:35:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1491510972766470149","full_text":"WHY ARE WE DOING THIS?  Main reason is: we don't know whether protons are stable particles---lasting literally forever---or whether they might decay sometimes.   It'd be interesting if they do.  A decaying proton would make a big flash of light in a detector like this.","favorite_count":"10","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 09 20:30:03 +0000 2022","id_str":"1491509723061014530","full_text":"It's Feb 9, 1987.  The Irvine-Michigan-Brookhaven experiment is sitting deep under Mentor, Ohio, monitoring a huge tank of ultrapure water to see if flashes of light occur within it. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1491509723061014530-FLLoMItXoAYXErl.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1491509723061014530-FLLoMItXoAYXErl.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"43","retweet_count":"8"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 09 14:17:51 +0000 2022","id_str":"1491416055742627842","full_text":"(You can download this 30-day plot and a longer 200-day version from <a href=\"https://physics.case.edu/realtime1987a-supernova-activities/\">https://physics.case.edu/realtime1987a-supernova-activities/</a>)","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Feb 09 14:17:50 +0000 2022","id_str":"1491416051305041926","full_text":"One thing we always want to know about a supernova is (a) how does its temperature change over time? and (b) how does its brightness change?  OK that's two things. Print out this image and make your own plots based on the first 30 days of tweeted data. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1491416051305041926-FLKR8raWYAEGRxf.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1491416051305041926-FLKR8raWYAEGRxf.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Tue Feb 08 14:05:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1491050440531877899","full_text":"This twitter feed is replaying all of the authentic 1987 news, observations, telegrams, and neutrinos---exactly 35 years after they happened.","favorite_count":"110","retweet_count":"36"},{"created_at":"Tue Feb 08 14:05:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1491050440527597568","full_text":"It is curated by @benmonreal, Ama Carney, and Adrian Lee of @PhysicsCWRU","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Feb 08 14:05:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1491050440439566336","full_text":"(Of course the star had exploded 160,000 years earlier.  1987 is when its first burst of light---and, remarkably, of neutrinos---arrived on Earth.)","favorite_count":"10","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Feb 08 14:01:14 +0000 2022","id_str":"1491049487619481601","full_text":"In February 1987, astronomers got their closest-ever look at an exploding star.","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Feb 07 20:02:56 +0000 2022","id_str":"1490778122324750337","full_text":"just tweeting some old plates. why? no reason <a href=\"https://twitter.com/_GlassStars_/status/1392524470292664323\">https://twitter.com/_GlassStars_/status/1392524470292664323</a>","favorite_count":"20","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Tue Feb 01 19:49:27 +0000 2022","id_str":"1488600402819837952","full_text":"@RealTime1987A is replaying the discovery and measurement of Supernova 1987A, 35 years after it happened.  Follow along!  Details coming soon.","favorite_count":"40","retweet_count":"19"},{"created_at":"Sun Apr 10 22:00:24 +0000 2022","id_str":"1513275730943258626","full_text":"B magnitude measured in South Africa to be 5.1","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Apr 10 18:45:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1513226564967837705","full_text":"McNaught takes a measurement from Siding Spring: M 3.5","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Apr 10 08:40:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1513074309744447488","full_text":"M. Morel measures magnitude from Rankin Park, N.S.W.: M 3.4","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Apr 09 19:00:41 +0000 2022","id_str":"1512868116119883785","full_text":"McNaught measures a magnitude of M 3.5 from Siding Spring","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Apr 08 22:00:47 +0000 2022","id_str":"1512551050867359749","full_text":"B magnitude was measured in South Africa: M 5.2","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Apr 08 16:01:40 +0000 2022","id_str":"1512460680250732550","full_text":"One story about its namesake, IAU president Jorge Sahade. In 1943, La Plata's German expat astronomer Alex Wilkins wanted his new graduate Sahade to train in the US. But where? He searched for a German-y name and found an \"Otto Struve\" at Yerkes. It worked out! <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1512460680250732550-FP1W-WPWQAMtrA9.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1512460680250732550-FP1W-WPWQAMtrA9.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Apr 08 15:09:14 +0000 2022","id_str":"1512447484664205315","full_text":"The Jorge Sahada is the fourth-largest telescope made by Boller &amp; Chivens.  (They also made the 100\" du Pont at Las Campanas, the 90\" Bok at KPNO and the UH 88\" on Mauna Kea.) <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1512447484664205315-FP1K-QgX0AYS77G.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1512447484664205315-FP1K-QgX0AYS77G.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Apr 08 14:17:08 +0000 2022","id_str":"1512434370925273096","full_text":"It's April 8, 1987.  A new observatory, Complejo Astron√≥mico El Leoncito (CASLEO) has JUST started regular observing operations LAST MONTH (!). IAUC 4361 today reports polarimetry from the new Jorge Sahade telescope. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1512434370925273096-FP0_CgUWYAAxpb7.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1512434370925273096-FP0_CgUWYAAxpb7.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"11","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Fri Apr 08 10:08:40 +0000 2022","id_str":"1512371844011241474","full_text":"McNaught measures magnitude from Siding Spring: M 3.6","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Apr 07 22:00:47 +0000 2022","id_str":"1512188663400120320","full_text":"B magnitude measured in South Africa to be 5.2","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Apr 07 11:35:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1512031188873093126","full_text":"McNaught measures magniude from Siding Spring: M 3.6","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Apr 06 15:25:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1511726684130750465","full_text":"McNaught measures magnitude from Siding Spring to be M 3.5","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Apr 06 14:00:22 +0000 2022","id_str":"1511705374746943494","full_text":"The Harvard Announcement Cards (1926--1964) coexisted with IAU circulars, then were replaced by them, then were forgotten. (CWRU's @kelvinsmithlib is the ONLY Ohio library that actually has the HACs, presumably with \"KICK ME (to the offsite warehouse)\" taped to the spine.)<br>5/5","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Apr 06 14:00:16 +0000 2022","id_str":"1511705353246978048","full_text":"This error is the source of reports of the premaximum plateau.  The present brightening of SN 1987A must therefore be regarded as another peculiarity of this object, without precedent among normal type-II SNe.\" <br>4/5","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Apr 06 14:00:11 +0000 2022","id_str":"1511705331470159879","full_text":"The pre-maximum light curve of SN 1940B contains no points, but it does contain five upper limits (HAC [Harvard Announcement Card] 576) which were erroneously reported as magnitudes in Bull. Soc. Ast. France 54, 185.  <br>3/5 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1511705331470159879-FPqn_RAXoAE0Nxw.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1511705331470159879-FPqn_RAXoAE0Nxw.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Apr 06 14:00:06 +0000 2022","id_str":"1511705308376309772","full_text":"\"The evidence for pre-maximum plateaux in the type-II supernovae 1940B and 1941A (cf. IAUC 4329, 4334) is not substantial.  The pre-maximum light curve of SN 1941A includes only one point and one upper limit (cf. HAC 522). <br>2/5 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1511705308376309772-FPqn97CX0AsDPW4.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1511705308376309772-FPqn97CX0AsDPW4.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Apr 06 14:00:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1511705285446049804","full_text":"SN 1987A seemed to sit at V=4.5 for ages and ages, didn't it?  It sure felt like forever if you had to tweet about it every day. People have been debating precedents for such a \"premaximum plateau\". Alain Porter comments in IAUC 4359: (thread!)<br>1/5 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1511705285446049804-FPqn8lCXIAMhjiE.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1511705285446049804-FPqn8lCXIAMhjiE.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"15","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Apr 05 22:00:49 +0000 2022","id_str":"1511463896703451139","full_text":"B magnitude measured in South Africa at M 5.3","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Apr 05 09:40:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1511277469218873352","full_text":"Seargent measures magnitude from The Entrance, N.S.W.: M 3.5","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Apr 04 22:00:45 +0000 2022","id_str":"1511101494518501387","full_text":"B magnitude measured in South Africa to be 5.3","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Apr 03 15:10:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1510635743416393735","full_text":"Visual magnitudes roundup: Garradd: 3.7, McNaught: 3.7, McNaught three hours later: 3.5 (!)","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Apr 02 11:05:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1510211699558830083","full_text":"McNaught measures a magnitude of M 3.6 from Siding Spring","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Apr 01 22:00:42 +0000 2022","id_str":"1510014317353181186","full_text":"B magnitude was measured in South Africa: M 5.4","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Apr 01 17:45:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1509949977413492747","full_text":"Campos measures magnitude from Durban, R.S.A.: M 3.8","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Apr 01 13:55:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1509892090997714962","full_text":"A. Beresfod measures magnitude from Adelaide, S. Australia: M 3.8","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Apr 01 11:05:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1509849311244345347","full_text":"R.H. McNaught measures magnitude from Siding Spring: M 3.7","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 31 17:45:03 +0000 2022","id_str":"1509587593465376768","full_text":"J. Campos measures magnitude from Durban, R.S.A.: M 3.8","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 31 11:01:16 +0000 2022","id_str":"1509485976908976135","full_text":"It's March 31, 1987.  Today in space-based astronomy, the USSR just launched the –ö–≤–∞–Ω—Ç-1 (Kvant = Quantum), the 2nd big module of the Mir space station.  Kvant-1 has a suite of UV and x-ray telescopes which (by reorienting the WHOLE STATION) will be pointed at 1987A later! <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1509485976908976135-FPLFf1AWUAE7JxY.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1509485976908976135-FPLFf1AWUAE7JxY.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1509485976908976135-FPLFf05XwAE5kVq.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1509485976908976135-FPLFf05XwAE5kVq.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 31 09:50:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1509468050541752321","full_text":"Visual magnitudes tonight from Australia: <br>Seargent 3.5<br>McNaught 3.8<br>Garradd 3.6","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 31 08:00:27 +0000 2022","id_str":"1509440473056047106","full_text":"Press release! ‚ÄúThis supernova is different from all others observed so far\".That is the unanimous conclusion of astronomers who have observed supernova 1987A in the Large Magellanic Cloud (LMC) with @ESO telescopes ... \" <a href=\"https://www.eso.org/public/news/eso8706/\">https://www.eso.org/public/news/eso8706/</a>","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 30 22:00:48 +0000 2022","id_str":"1509289565374320650","full_text":"B magnitude was measured in South Africa to be 5.5","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 30 15:00:55 +0000 2022","id_str":"1509183900945367041","full_text":"At M = 3.8, 1987A is maybe the 400th-brightest object in the sky. <br>400th largest US city: Merced, CA<br>400th QS-ranked world university: Strasbourg/La Trobe/CU-Denver (tied)","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 30 09:40:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1509103144126619651","full_text":"Visual magnitudes roundup: <br>Seargent 3.6<br>McNaught 3.7<br>Beresford 3.9","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 29 09:50:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1508743273170485250","full_text":"Visual magnitudes roundup: Seargent 3.8, Garradd 3.7, McNaught 3.8, Beresford 3.9","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 28 22:00:50 +0000 2022","id_str":"1508564798811820040","full_text":"B magnitude of 5.5 measured in South Africa","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 28 19:40:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1508529363314266130","full_text":"Campos measures magnitude at Durban, R.S.A. to be M 3.9","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 28 16:15:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1508477773224022021","full_text":"Now that we're past 30 days, the high-intensity daily-supernova-edutainment content will be slowing down a bit.  What's next? a) BRIGHTENING b) x-rays and gamma rays (fellow instrument nerds, you will meet NEW INSTRUMENTS), and c)  a July 6--8 ESO conference at Garching","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 28 14:00:50 +0000 2022","id_str":"1508444004366618625","full_text":"\"I would like this gift to help CWRU physicists build astro, astroparticle, and neutrino physics instrumentation, like I read about on Twitter, in 1987\" might confuse them, but you will not detect one hint of annoyance. That is how Midwestern Nice works and they are true masters","favorite_count":"7","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 28 13:40:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1508438765416722441","full_text":"I do not know what happens if you call the giving office and say \"I would like my gift to enable Ben Monreal to spend way too much time on Twitter\" but you can try, they're very nice","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Mon Mar 28 13:30:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1508436252533698560","full_text":"It's March 28, 1987.  Thanks so much for following along this far.  I don't have a tip jar, but Case Western Reserve University is a fine nonprofit institution which can put donations large and small to good use (<a href=\"https://case.edu/give/\">https://case.edu/give/</a>) for education and research.","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Mar 27 22:00:24 +0000 2022","id_str":"1508202300883537921","full_text":"B magnitude of 5.6 measured in South Africa","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Mar 27 17:45:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1508138037397573636","full_text":"Campos measures magnitude at Durban, R.S.A.: M 3.9","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Mar 27 10:35:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1508029820139151360","full_text":"Seargent measures magnitude at The Entrance, N.S.W.: M 3.9","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sun Mar 27 09:10:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1508008432716193794","full_text":"G.Garradd measures magnitude at Tamworth, N.S.W.: M 4.1","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Mar 26 21:25:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507831010909634568","full_text":"Campos measures magnitude at Durban, R.S.A.: M 4.0","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Sat Mar 26 18:36:09 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507788513701507082","full_text":"It's March 26th---the 30 day mark of SN1987A.  If you or your students have been plotting along at <a href=\"https://physics.case.edu/real-time-supernova/\">https://physics.case.edu/real-time-supernova/</a> I would LOVE to see your light curves.","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 25 20:00:18 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507447302906126341","full_text":"Let's end today with a two paragraphs from Arnett (Commun. ACM 28, 1985): one on the 1987 computing hardware relevant to the previous thread, one on software and dataviz. <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1507447302906126341-FOuHVXiWQAk3py_.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1507447302906126341-FOuHVXiWQAk3py_.png\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1507447302906126341-FOuHVVxXEBc8Hk1.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1507447302906126341-FOuHVVxXEBc8Hk1.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 25 17:30:28 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507409594062192647","full_text":"\"It's plotted on a scale covering 15 magnitudes, how is that 'good'?\". Look buddy, astronomers will keep making \"the error is in the exponent\" jokes about themselves until AT LEAST say 1998--2000. Some physicists will stop after, say, WMAP DR2.  Some won't &lt;sigh&gt;.<br>6/6","favorite_count":"11","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 25 17:30:22 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507409572008546305","full_text":"In fact Arnett can simulate a shock propagating through this model (in a 200-zone 1D model, with an adaptive mesh that adds detail to the top of the photosphere). When he injects a 2x10^51 erg explosion, he gets a pretty good light curve?<br>5/6 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1507409572008546305-FOtlBIrWYAE2CTn.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1507409572008546305-FOtlBIrWYAE2CTn.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1507409572008546305-FOtlBJ6WQAkG7nv.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1507409572008546305-FOtlBJ6WQAkG7nv.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 25 17:30:17 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507409548478451720","full_text":"An evolution model (taking into account that the LMC has lower metal abundances than the Milky Way) can give the late-time structure of such a star, and it's small enough to let the shock break out quickly ... <br>4/6 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1507409548478451720-FOtk_wIXoAQnoqc.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1507409548478451720-FOtk_wIXoAQnoqc.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 25 17:30:11 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507409524554141698","full_text":"A 15 Msun B3 I star can evolve from birth to supernova in the \"right\" amount of time (less than 20 My) given the local star formation history ...  <br>3/6 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1507409524554141698-FOtk-VnXsAUxYbp.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1507409524554141698-FOtk-VnXsAUxYbp.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 25 17:30:05 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507409500453670913","full_text":"That note might sound like sour grapes, but the paper established that a 15 Msun B3 I star would make sense as the progenitor (just LIKE SK -69 202 but not the same ONE).  After all: <br>2/6","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 25 17:30:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507409478567743489","full_text":"Along with all these in-press papers whose attitude is \"what a weird supernova!\", David Arnett's \"Supernova Theory and Supernova 1987A\" arrived today at ApJ (ApJ 319) calmly explaining that early data matches theory, given that OBVIOUSLY it WASN'T SK -69 202, so ... er ... <br>1/6 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1507409478567743489-FOtk7sHXEHwdyLl.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1507409478567743489-FOtk7sHXEHwdyLl.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 25 15:14:19 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507375330260004871","full_text":"<div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1507375330260004871-FOtF3mXVcAE9m6x.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1507375330260004871-FOtF3mXVcAE9m6x.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 25 15:09:54 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507374221210624003","full_text":"OK that's your Morning Thread! Almost sounds like it's too early and we haven't learned a darned thing yet!  However, there will be an Afternoon Thread focusing on Arnett (ApJ 319), so keep clicking reload obsessively until then thx<br>11/11 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1507374221210624003-FOtE3V0XoAswsYg.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1507374221210624003-FOtE3V0XoAswsYg.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 25 15:09:48 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507374195705008132","full_text":"Fabian et. al (same issue!) suggests that maybe Sk -69 202's close binary partner exploded, making a weird supernova that includes hydrogen blasted off the supergiant!<br>10/11","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 25 15:09:43 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507374173945008135","full_text":"Shigeyama et al (Nature 328, submitted April 9) discuss explosions of a 6 Msun helium star (which they had simulated previously) OR a 20 Msun blue supergiant (which they haven't).<br>9/11","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 25 15:09:38 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507374152503775243","full_text":"McCray, Shull, and Sutherland just submitted \"Inside Supernova 1987\" (ApJ 317) is also a huge suite of x-ray/gamma ray predictions.<br>8/11","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 25 15:09:33 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507374130848571402","full_text":"Anyway, they predict a lot will be learned from whether the supernova brightens (in weeks or months) AND the nature and timing of the subsequent x-ray/gamma-ray display.<br>7/11","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 25 15:09:27 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507374109294047242","full_text":"So they're writing about how maybe we're looking at a \"Type IIb\" supernova, whose progenitor (NOT SK -69 202 STOP SAYING THAT) had shed most of its hydrogen; in this case the rapid early reddening is because we're looking at a helium, not hydrogen, photosphere.<br>6/11","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 25 15:09:22 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507374087777230856","full_text":"Woolsey et. al (ApJ 318, in revision already) think the shock time (3h between Kamiokande's neutrinos and McNaught's photons) is inexplicably short ... for a red giant! (Because TypeII supernovae are red giants, and everyone knows blue supergiant Sk -69 202 didn't explode.)<br>5/11","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 25 15:09:17 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507374066277179395","full_text":"Wampler et. al. (A&amp;A 182) think Mont Blanc got the neutrino time AND Jones's that last \"nondetect\" was mistaken!<br>4/11","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 25 15:09:12 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507374044722704386","full_text":"1987A is the first system that can tell us the TIME between the collapse and the shock breakout.  Start your stopwatch at the neutrinos; stop it somewhere between Jones' last nondetect and Mcnaught's first detection plate. Easy, right?  Not quite.<br>3/11","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 25 15:09:07 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507374023273029648","full_text":"The exploding core we talked about yesterday? That happened millions of kilometers BELOW the photosphere. There's nothing for Ian Shelton to see until the shock (moving much slower than light) \"breaks out\"---reaching the photosphere, heating it, inflating it.<br>2/11","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 25 15:09:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507374001722646536","full_text":"It's March 25th, 1987. Day 29. SN1987A is brightening slowly and steadily but its color evolution has slowed.  You're sitting at the ApJ or Nature editorial desk.  Maybe there's a paper in the submissions pile that'll tell you what's up! <br>1/11","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 25 11:45:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507322664272248832","full_text":"Seargent measures magnitude at The Entrance, N.S.W. to be M 3.8","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 25 09:40:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507291202793742337","full_text":"Beresford in Adelaide, S. Australia takes a magnitude measurement: M 4.0","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Fri Mar 25 02:40:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507185510036525056","full_text":"J. Campos in Durban, R.S.A. measures magnitude: M 4.0","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 24 22:00:48 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507115238080004103","full_text":"B magnitude was measured in South Africa at a magnitude of 5.6","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 24 19:10:16 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507072321294684168","full_text":"160,000 light years away, a little 20-km ball of matter, undergoing a nuclear and gravitational cataclysm almost too violent to imagine, sent us a message. Almost by accident, we were listening, and we heard it.  <br>15/15 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1507072321294684168-FOoySk-WYAMI4mq.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1507072321294684168-FOoySk-WYAMI4mq.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1507072321294684168-FOoySk8WUA00eZo.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1507072321294684168-FOoySk8WUA00eZo.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"11","retweet_count":"2"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 24 19:10:10 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507072298481860613","full_text":"But I think we can wrap up and call 1980s core-collapse theory a SMASHING SUCCESS, predicting the neutrino arrival times, energies, and fluxes better than anyone could have hoped.  <br>14/15","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 24 19:10:05 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507072276436557831","full_text":"then you can explain EVERY IMB and KII neutrino arrival time.  (IMPORTANT NOTE: Nature does not have quite the highest-impact must-read reputation in physics/astro that it does in some fields.) <br><br>13/15 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1507072276436557831-FOoyP7TXIBId0--.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1507072276436557831-FOoyP7TXIBId0--.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 24 19:09:59 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507072252130598921","full_text":"I want this feed to avoid the \"Whig history\" of focusing on successes and confirmations. There's plenty of weird see-what-sticks interpretation going on! Harwit, Biermann, Meyer, Wasserman (Nature v328) suggest that if the neutrinos are arriving in 8.9ms pulsar-y bursts ...<br>12/15","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 24 19:09:54 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507072230513074176","full_text":"Meanwhile the vague suspicion that Mont Blanc is too weird to believe is being made quantitative.  Shaeffer, Declais, and Jullian (Nature v300, submitting April 2), say Mont Blanc's signal implies a 3x10^54 erg burst that is not believable.<br>11/15","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 24 19:09:49 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507072209004736514","full_text":"\"... the observations of supernova neutrinos represent therefore a great triumph for astrophysical theory.\"<br>10/15","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 24 19:09:44 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507072187378937860","full_text":"\"The temperatures and fluxes inferred here are in remarkable agreement with the standard theoretical ideas of how stars collapse and supernovae are formed ...<br>9/15","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 24 19:09:39 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507072165870546950","full_text":"They state a total neutrino energy of 3x10^52 and are, AFAICT, the first to put error bars on it.  (\"Why does Nature publish THIS analysis rather than one of the model- and evolution-aware versions\"?  (a) because it's SHORT and (b) because it's PRINCETONIANS)<br>8/15","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 24 19:09:33 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507072144181710848","full_text":"Bahcall, Piran, Press, and Spergel (again in Nature!) try to get all the information---event energies and directions---out of the detected neutrinos with maximum likelihood methods.  Note that \"what neutrino flux arrived?\" is a different question than \"what core collapsed?\"<br>7/15","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 24 19:09:28 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507072122157416460","full_text":"Burrows and Lattimer (ApJ 318, submitted April 6) say \"Surprisingly, as Figure 1 shows, the models for the data.\", with a slight preference for non-convecting models with a fast rise, adding up to \"some multiple of 10^52 ergs\".<br>6/15 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1507072122157416460-FOoyG97X0AYtEhG.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1507072122157416460-FOoyG97X0AYtEhG.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 24 19:09:22 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507072098115665921","full_text":"Bruenn's PRL (submitted May 22) maps out the IMB and Kamioka neutrino arrival-times (just the early ones!) and argues that a small-ish iron core has collapsed, but notes his model's neutrinos are lower-energy than Woolsey's.  Total energy radiated?  8.2x10^52 ergs.<br>5/15 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1507072098115665921-FOoyFguXsAcOubz.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1507072098115665921-FOoyFguXsAcOubz.png\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1507072098115665921-FOoyFiDXsAcyPY0.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1507072098115665921-FOoyFiDXsAcyPY0.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 24 19:09:17 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507072073625128967","full_text":"The neutrino energies support Wilson and Mayles over Hillebrand; Burrows and Lattimer's proto-neutron-star-relaxation model has about the right burst duration but undershoots the energies and rates.<br>4/15 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1507072073625128967-FOoyEJ_XEAgzohF.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1507072073625128967-FOoyEJ_XEAgzohF.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 24 19:09:11 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507072050552356868","full_text":"Sato (whose PC-9801 you saw earlier) and Suzuki's March 11 PRL adds up the Kamiokande neutrino energies (it's submitted before IMB reports) and gets 4.8x10^52 ergs---consistent with Wilson's 15Msun model runs.<br>3/15","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 24 19:09:06 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507072028943265794","full_text":"Remember the March 3 IAUC where Bahcall, Dar, and Piran's gave neutrino predictions and added \"we wrote this before Mont Blanc reported!\"  They'd just sent that to Nature, where it appeared March 12 with a new note \"we received this before the Kamikakande reported!\" lol<br>2/15","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 24 19:09:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507072007279722501","full_text":"It's March 24. Following our recent tweets, we know that up-to-date computational tools are on hand.  Who has used them?  What have we learned?  (I'll tweet core/neutrinos today and envelope/star tomorrow.)  T H R E A D<br>1/15","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 24 17:40:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1507049614163206148","full_text":"J. Campos in Durban, R.S.A. measures magnitude: M 4.1","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 24 13:28:55 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506986418001829888","full_text":"<div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1506986418001829888-FOnkKQnX0AcouCK.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1506986418001829888-FOnkKQnX0AcouCK.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"47","retweet_count":"5"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 24 10:05:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506935108741304322","full_text":"Seargent at The Entrance, N.S.W. measures magnitude: M 3.9","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 24 10:05:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506935108116398085","full_text":"Beresford in Adelaide, S. Australia measures a magnitude: M 4.1","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Thu Mar 24 04:50:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506855834239787008","full_text":"Polarization of SN now close to expected galactic interstellar polarization.","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 23 16:16:03 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506666092583964675","full_text":"OK I am leaving out like six or seven other key papers BUT THE POINT IS: supernova theorists in 1987 are 100% ready to interpret the neutrino data, despite not understanding the outgoing shock all the optical astronomers are looking at.<br>12/12","favorite_count":"9","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 23 16:15:57 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506666067418136584","full_text":"The authors point out (a) this may all be wrong if the protoneutron star convects, and (b) the results make them more pessimistic about ever detecting a neutrino burst.  (Burrows' \"On detecting stellar collapse with neutrinos\", ApJ 283 (1984) had already been pessimistic!)<br>11/12 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1506666067418136584-FOjAzcHXIAgAZ2R.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1506666067418136584-FOjAzcHXIAgAZ2R.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 23 16:15:51 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506666043124727817","full_text":"That relaxation includes neutrino (and antineutrino) emission!  So, from \"The Birth of Neutron Stars\" ApJ 307 (1986), here's Figs 19 and 20.  (\"mu\" represents all non-electron-flavor neutrinos and antineutrinos.)<br>10/12 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1506666043124727817-FOjAyDhXEAQcIt_.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1506666043124727817-FOjAyDhXEAQcIt_.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 23 16:15:46 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506666019380736003","full_text":"But you may have noticed many of Wilson's simulations end after ~1 second. Burrows and Lattimer at SUNY Stony Brook have a code optimized for the *next* 20 second as the proto-neutron-star \"relaxes\".<br>9/12 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1506666019380736003-FOjAwrFXwAcY0Y7.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1506666019380736003-FOjAwrFXwAcY0Y7.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 23 16:15:40 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506665995682951169","full_text":"... and in THERE you find the neutrino energy spectrum---an immediately useful plot you can compare to the Kamiokande-II and IMB papers.  (Make sure to leave time to argue about whether IMB knows their energy-dependent detection efficiency.)<br>8/12 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1506665995682951169-FOjAvQAXoAEdFdP.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1506665995682951169-FOjAvQAXoAEdFdP.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 23 16:15:34 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506665971343405058","full_text":"Woolsey, Wilson, Mayle (\"Gravitational Collapse and the Cosmic Antineutrino Background\", ApJ 302 1986). reanalyzing those same sims, wants to know about the net effect of billions of supernovae, whose rate is given in supernovae per cubic centimeter per second (!)<br>7/12 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1506665971343405058-FOjAt5gWQAQ-EC3.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1506665971343405058-FOjAt5gWQAQ-EC3.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 23 16:15:29 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506665948513771520","full_text":"\"The success or failure of the shock in escaping the iron core depends on subtle effects\"; but Wilson tries to interpret what's happening INWARD of the shock anyway---because that's enough to get a neutrino-emission prediction.<br>6/12","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 23 16:15:23 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506665925793259526","full_text":"Anyway, Wilson et. al. find that these iron cores (except the lightest) collapse when electron capture and iron-photodisintegration and remove the pressure support.  The innermost 0.5M‚äô hits nuclear density first‚Äîin milliseconds‚Äîand launches the outgoing shock wave.<br>5/12 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1506665925793259526-FOjArL6XEAIFlox.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1506665925793259526-FOjArL6XEAIFlox.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 23 16:15:18 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506665901499768844","full_text":"(As an aside, I know ALMOST NOTHING about Barbara Zimmerman and neither does Google.  She was Caltech staff; this is a picture of her; can someone please visit Fowler's archived papers at Caltech and write a Wikipedia article?)<br>4/12 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1506665901499768844-FOjApzqXsAkAYpE.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1506665901499768844-FOjApzqXsAkAYpE.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"8","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 23 16:15:12 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506665877118361608","full_text":"The \"A/B/C\" models have different nuclear physics, particularly disagreeing about 12C+Œ±‚Üí16O+Œ≥.  Everyone in this field dotes on Willy Fowler, Georgeanne Caughlan, and Barbara Zimmerman's periodically-updated (and CHARMING) nuclear data compilations.<br>3/12 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1506665877118361608-FOjAoPjXoAErQhj.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1506665877118361608-FOjAoPjXoAErQhj.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1506665877118361608-FOjAoQPXIAI0caS.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1506665877118361608-FOjAoQPXIAI0caS.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1506665877118361608-FOjAoRyXMAkJfU3.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1506665877118361608-FOjAoRyXMAkJfU3.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"5","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 23 16:15:06 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506665850861928453","full_text":"Wilson, Mayle, Woolsey, and Weaver (\"Stellar core collapse and supernova\", Ann.NYAcadSci 1986) report the following runs.  Notice that (e.g.) 25 M‚äô stars are contemplated as having anywhere from 1.4‚Äì2 M‚äô iron cores.  That reflects uncertainty in stellar evolution theory.<br>2/12 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1506665850861928453-FOjAm4NXoAMdwNu.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1506665850861928453-FOjAm4NXoAMdwNu.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 23 16:15:00 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506665827659038731","full_text":"It's March 22, 1987. 1987A continues to brighten. You're sitting in your Northern Hemisphere theory office---no telescopes, no CCDs, no PMTs. Fortunately, you have something EVEN BETTER---a stack of 1985-1986 theory papers! Maybe there's a collapsing 20M‚äô supergiant model!<br>1/12","favorite_count":"11","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 23 14:05:04 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506633127061606407","full_text":"\"Things have been pretty routine here on Las Campanas lately ... nightly observing, ping-pong in the 2.5m Coud√© room, the occasional Supernova of the Century, scorpion races on the weekends, and so on.  In other words, the usual.\" -- Jaymie Matthews <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1506633127061606407-FOii2CuXMAUxtE1.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1506633127061606407-FOii2CuXMAUxtE1.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1506633127061606407-FOii2DdWQAo9FK7.png\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1506633127061606407-FOii2DdWQAo9FK7.png\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"11","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 23 11:05:02 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506587821015973888","full_text":"R.H. McNaught at Coonabarabran, N.S.W. estimates the magnitude: M 4.1","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Wed Mar 23 04:50:01 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506493447280242689","full_text":"V.M. Blanco claims Sanduleak -69 202 is a type B3 Ia star and star 2 is type B0 V.","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 22 18:11:42 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506332808909922310","full_text":"Anyway, even in 1987, supernova hydrodynamic simulation work is a perpetual battle between \"wish for higher resolution\" and \"finite computer resources\" and \"tolerate approximate results\".  Tune in tomorrow for ... tolerable approximate results! <br>13/13","favorite_count":"6","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 22 18:11:36 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506332784633257992","full_text":"Wilson at LLNL probably had access to a CRAY-1.  Anyone know what Steven Bruenn was using at Florida Atlantic?  <br>12/13 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1506332784633257992-FOeRrsIX0AcdyvG.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1506332784633257992-FOeRrsIX0AcdyvG.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"4","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 22 18:11:30 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506332757194125323","full_text":"To illustrate the computing limits, the Sato group in Tokyo has an 8 MHz PC-9801, running BASIC or MS-DOS, with a 1.2MB floppy drive; a modem connects to a mainframe (I think a HITAC S-810)<br>11/13 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1506332757194125323-FOeRqNAXIAEG_La.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1506332757194125323-FOeRqNAXIAEG_La.jpg\"></a></li><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1506332757194125323-FOeRqLaXMAkASuJ.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1506332757194125323-FOeRqLaXMAkASuJ.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 22 18:11:24 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506332732330233858","full_text":"It doesn't sound like a lot, right? You're sitting there reading tweets on a phone with a 200 gigaflop GPU.  A bunch of 10x100 matrix multiplications is NOTHING in 2020.<br>10/13","favorite_count":"3","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 22 18:11:19 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506332710771507205","full_text":"(The pre-Manhattan-Project bomb feasibility calculations were one-group calculations; I think by the end of the war they could do three-group.) <br>9/13","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 22 18:11:14 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506332689212878848","full_text":"\"Multigroup\" means tracking neutrinos in groups of different energies.  Bruenn can slice a star into 50-100 radial shells and track 10 neutrino energy groups (in three flavors!).<br>8/13","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 22 18:11:08 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506332667494780929","full_text":"Bruenn's 1985 paper on the MGFLDA (MultiGroup Flux Limited Diffusion Approximation) code has some details worth pointing out.  That's a pure Boltzmann solver, with aspects of the neutrino transport benchmarked against Monte Carlo (from Tubbs, also a weapons lab guy).<br>7/13","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 22 18:11:03 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506332645751463949","full_text":"There are direct connections---James R. Wilson, for one, spent 25 years doing \"classified work\" at Lawrence Livermore before a 1968 sabbatical at Cambridge let him jump to astro.  So the 1970s and 80s, we're doing nonviolent physics with this bomb-inspired code.<br>6/13","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 22 18:10:58 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506332623764926473","full_text":"Long-distance energy transport is a key behavior of NEUTRONS in an ATOM BOMB. The famous Los Alamos T-5 desktop calculator division existed for Boltzmann-equation-with-long-distance-energy-propagation very similar to a supernova problem.<br>5/13 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1506332623764926473-FOeRigYWUAoBEK6.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1506332623764926473-FOeRigYWUAoBEK6.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 22 18:10:53 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506332600855576586","full_text":"But we CAN compute all this, because we've done it before, in less pleasant circumstances. <br>4/13","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"0"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 22 18:10:47 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506332578579681282","full_text":"Another new-ish detail: the early-70s discovery of weak neutral currents (i.e. Z boson scattering) gave neutrinos a way to exert hydrodynamic forces---they do long-range momentum transfers as well long-range energy deposits.  <br>3/13 <div class=\"gallery\"><ul><li><a href=\"../../tweets_media/1506332578579681282-FOeRf3HXEAclQtk.jpg\"><img src=\"../../tweets_media/1506332578579681282-FOeRf3HXEAclQtk.jpg\"></a></li></ul></div>","favorite_count":"1","retweet_count":"1"},{"created_at":"Tue Mar 22 18:10:42 +0000 2022","id_str":"1506332554848346112","full_text":"Neutrinos aren't like that.  A jump in neutrino production at r might exert a force on some matter 10 km further out. Every cell in your data array is coupled to every other cell! Computational steps that used to be \"add vectors\" need to change to \"multiply matrices\".<br>2/13","favorite_count":"2","retweet_count":"0"}]